<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian President Leaves for Visit to Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today left for a two-day visit to Germany which will include talks
with German Chancellor Helmut Kohl on a draft accord on
Russia's relationship with the NATO military alliance.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders are also expected to discuss bilateral economic
ties, European security as well as Russia's full membership of the
Group of Seven industrial nations, the World Trade Organization
and the Paris Club group of creditors, Sergei Yastrzhembsky, the
presidential press secretary, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The return of art treasures seized by the Soviet Red
Army from the Nazis during World War II would also be on the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries have been complicated by
the Russian parliament's refusal to allow the return of the World
War II trophy art.
</P>
<P>
Later today, Russia's Federal Council, the upper house of
parliament, is to debate whether to back the lower house in
overruling Yeltsin's veto of a draft law which says the art should
stay in Russia.
</P>
<P>
After talks with Kohl on Thursday, Yeltsin is expected to
receive a "Man of the Year" award from the German media. He is to
return home on Friday.
</P>
<P>
A report by Russia's Itar-Tass news agency quoted Kohl as
saying that German-Russian relations are based on trust and
cooperation in many fields and both sides are making efforts to
broaden the close partnership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
