<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Housing Construction Declines in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) --As interest rates rising, U.S.
housing construction started to drop in March #,according to a
report from the U.S. Department of Commerce today.
</P>
<P>
Housing starts dropped 6.4 percent to a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 1.42 million units, both single-family homes and
apartments, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The decline is regarded as the worst in three months, and also
was somewhat larger than that expected by economists.
</P>
<P>
The level of construction in February, a seasonally adjusted
annual rate of 1.52 million, was the highest in nearly three
years, stimulated by low mortgage rates and comparatively mild
weather.
</P>
<P>
However, mortgage rates began rising in March, anticipating
monetary tightening by the Federal Reserve near the end of the
month. Fixed-rate, 30-year mortgages now are averaging above 8
percent for the first time since last fall.
</P>
<P>
The monthly decline was focused in single-family construction,
which fell 8.3 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
1.22 million homes. Apartment construction rose 1.3 percent to a
seasonally adjusted 308,000 units.
</P>
<P>
Housing permits, a barometer of future construction, ebbed 1.5
percent in March, with single-family homes registering a 5.8
percent decline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
