<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Gains Big Earnings to $1.5 bln in 1st Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Ford Motor Co. announced today
its first-quarter profit more than doubled from a year ago to 1.5
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. second largest automaker's revenues totaled 36.2
billion dollars, a 3 percent increase from 35.2 billion dollars in
the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
Ford's automotive operations earned 1 billion dollars, a
sevenfold increase from the 142 million dollars a year ago. Its
U.S. automotive profits were 836 million dollars as compared with
48 million dollars in the first three months last year.
</P>
<P>
Ford attributed its improved performance to sales of
higher-profit vehicles and its Ford 2000 cost-cutting program.
</P>
<P>
The company's earnings from its international automotive
operations were less impressive, but still showed improvement at
168 million dollars, up from 94 million dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The improvements stem from cost reductions, the successful
launch of new products and a resurgence of Ford's business in
South America, the company said.
</P>
<P>
In South America, which has been a major money drain on Ford,
Ford cut its loss to 47 million dollars compared with a 60 million
dollars loss a year ago. Ford has not made a profit there since
the second quarter of 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
