<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR to Preserve People's Freedom: Tung Chee Hwa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) has the strongest
determination to preserve the freedoms that the people of Hong
Kong currently enjoy, said Tung Chee Hwa, Chief Executive of the
HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Addressing at a dinner held by the Canadian Chamber of Commerce
this evening, Tung said he will assure everyone in the audience
that the amendments to the two ordinances are not aimed at any
particular groups of persons or any individual organizations.
</P>
<P>
Last week the Chief Executive's Office issued a document to
solicit Hong Kong people's suggestions on the amendments to the
Societies Ordinance and the Public Order Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
Tung said peaceful and lawful demonstrations can and must be
allowed to continue, adding, "I see public demonstrations as a way
for people to express their views and public demonstrations are
now a part of Hong Kong's culture."
</P>
<P>
On the Societies Ordinance, he said that most of the countries
in the world are sensitive about influences of foreign political
parties on their domestic political scene.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Do we want foreigners or foreign political parties to
influence political direction in Hong Kong? I believe that the
community will not want this to happen. Indeed, we should not let
this happen."
</P>
<P>
With regard to the Public Order Ordinance, the issue here is to
find the balance between the rights of individuals who want to
demonstrate and the stability and convenience of society as a
whole, he said.
</P>
<P>
"I hope the consultative exercise will bring our community
together to reach a broad consensus as to the direction we wish to
take and the kind of community we want to live in the 21st
century," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
