<HEADLINE> DPRK, South Korea, US Meet on Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK), the Republic of Korea (ROK) and the United States
met on Wednesday for the second time in two months on the proposed
four-party peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place in U.N. Plaza Hotel across the street of
the United Nations. A South Korean press officer with access to
the meeting said the DPRK and ROK officials shook hands at the
beginning of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Song Yong Shik, ROK Deputy Foreign Minister for Political
Affairs, said "we are in the middle of the warm spring and the
meeting will be a very cozy one."
</P>
<P>
DPRK head of delegation Kim Gye Gwan, Vice Minister of Foreign
Affairs, said "we hope we will come out with good result."
</P>
<P>
Noticing that there 21 correspondent at presence, he said:
"There are 21 correspondents, they are moving towards 21 century."
</P>
<P>
The South Korean press officer said they are expecting answer
from DPRK regarding a U.S.-South Korea proposal on a four-party
negotiations on a new security arrangement to replace the 1953
armistice which ended fighting in the Korea peninsula. The four
parties are DPRK, ROK, the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
Leading the U.S. delegation is Charles Kartman, acting U.S.
assistant secretary of state of East Asia and Pacific affairs.
</P>
<P>
Last month, U.S. and South Korean representatives briefed the
North Koreans in New York about the peace talks. The DPRK said
they needed more time to study it and asked for another round of
discussions.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to last for only one day. DPRK and
U.S. delegation are going to meet on Friday without the South
Korea to discuss such issues as opening liaison offices in each
other's capitals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
