<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Mutual Fund Sales Up Despite Market Jitters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Canada's mutual fund industry
posted its record retirement savings plan season this year, taking
in 5.1 billion U.S. dollars from investors last month despite a
slide in stock and bond prices.
</P>
<P>
March's inflows to funds brought sales in the first three
months of the year to 16 billion dollars, reports said today.
</P>
<P>
This figure surpassed the previous record of 14.3 billion
dollars in the first quarter of 1994, when low interest rates and
hot stock market sent investors into mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
Despite the big sales, Canada's fund industry assets rose only
1.7 billion dollars to a record 168.8 billion last month.
</P>
<P>
Higher interest rates in the U.S. have sent stock and bond
prices tumbling, wiping about 3.4 billion dollars off the value in
mutual funds in March.
</P>
<P>
During the month, the average Canadian equity fund lost 3.8
percent while the average domestic balanced fund fell 2.6 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
