<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Passenger Terminal Building Fitout Highlights Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's new airport at Chek
Lap Kok is transforming rapidly from a construction site to an
operating facility, the Airport Authority (AA) said today.
</P>
<P>
The massive passenger terminal building is more apparent in
this field, where the fitout stage is well under way with many
services already reaching their commissioning stage in the run-up
to airport opening in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
The transportation center is taking shape at the front door.
This will provide road and rail links to Kowloon and Central Hong
Kong, offering passengers, workers and visitors a level of
convenience available at very few airports worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Inside the departure hall, the first of 288 baggage check-in
desks, arranged in nine islands, are being tested. Final fittings
and adjustments are being made to conveyor belts that form part of
the largest airport baggage handling system in the world.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the system is designed to serve 35 million
passengers per year and 13,680 departure bags per hour, almost
twice the number handled by the existing system at the current
Hong Kong Kai Tak Airport. And the system has been designed so
that all baggage should be reclaimed within 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
The departure hall and the northern concourse are the sites of
many benchmark fittings. With most of these trials successfully
completed, the fitout is continuing throughout the remainder of
the building, including interior architecture features such as
granite flooring, painting and soffit linings in the ceiling, AA
officials said.
</P>
<P>
The passenger terminal is designed to be a low-energy user
compared to other commercial buildings in Hong Kong. Its roof,
for example, is five times more energy-efficient than a typical
Hong Kong roof, and acts as a vast insulator. Ceiling skylights
and reflectors provide generous amounts of natural light to main
halls and lounges which reduces the amount of artificial light
required.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
