<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Inflation Rises to 19.9 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's monthly inflation rose to
19.9 percent in March amid warnings from local banks and economists
that the economy is facing serious inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
Market analyst Jason Moore today said, ''the inflation figure for
March is pretty well within our expectations and conforms our
forecast that inflation will be on an upward trend for the
foreseeable future.''
</P>
<P>
It is now widely accepted that inflation will continue rising, and
could exceed 20 percent by mid-year before dipping thereafter to end
the year pegged at between 18 and 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
Inflation, which reached a seven-year low of nearly 14 percent in
November 1996, was pegged at 15.8 percent in January this year, and
rose further to 19 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
The sharp rise in inflation last month was mainly attributed to
the knock-on effects of the increase in fruit and vegetable prices,
which on average soared by about 50 percent following heavy rains
which destroyed some crops, causing a slight shortage on the local
market. enditem

