<HEADLINE> Irish Government Popularity Drops in Pre-Election Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The chances of the Irish
government winning a second term suffered another setback today
when an opinion poll reveals that the popularity of Labor Party, a
major partner in the three-party coalition, dropped sharply in
Dublin.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the Irish Evening Herald newspaper,
was published amid renewed speculation that Prime Minister John
Bruton was likely to call an early election on May 23 in a bid to
capitalize on the country's favorable economic situation, press
reports from Dublin said.
</P>
<P>
The results of this latest poll showed that the Labor Party,
whose leader is Irish Foreign Minister Dick Spring, could lose up
to six seats in Dublin, where about one third of the country's
parliamentary seats are located.
</P>
<P>
The Labor's support in Dublin, which usually holds the key to a
general election victory, has fallen 26 percent in 1992 elections
to 14 percent this month and that Labor's share of parliamentary
seats could drop from 32 to 26.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the poll also revealed that the opposition Fianna
Fail and Progressive Democrat parties, which hold a six-point lead
over the coalition government in most opinion polls, were gaining
more support ahead of the general election.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts say that the current situation would be a
severe blow to the government's chances of rebuilding the
coalition of the Fine Gael party, Labor Party and the Democratic
Left. 
</P>
</TEXT>
