<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daimler-Benz Turnover Up 12 Percent in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Germany's largest industrial concern
Daimler-Benz said today group sales in the first quarter of 1997
rose 12 percent to 26 billion marks (1 U.S. dollar=1.9 German
mark) and promised further improvements over the year.
</P>
<P>
The company, which achieved a turnaround in profits in 1996
from a loss of 200 million marks to a profit of 2.4 billion marks,
said the achievement was partly a result of extensive cost cutting,
particularly through portfolio restructuring and divestment of
chronic loss-making areas.
</P>
<P>
Daimler is planning to raise 1.1 billion marks through a
convertible bond issue, convertible into ordinary shares by 2002,
to strengthen its capital base for future growth.
</P>
<P>
From 1997 through 1999, the company said it was planning fixed
asset investment worldwide of nearly 20 billion marks, with a
further 15 billion marks earmarked for research and development.
</P>
<P>
In a profit and loss breakdown for 1996, Daimler said
passenger car production at Mercedes made a profit of 3.1 billion
marks, with commercial vehicles showing a loss of 400 million
marks.
</P>
<P>
Daimler-Benz Aerospace lost 196 million marks, compared with a
7.2 billion mark loss in 1995.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, Mercedes-Benz sold 154,000
cars, a 4 percent increase over the first quarter last year,
boosting revenues by 11 percent to 11.4 billion marks, the company
said.
</P>
<P>
Daimler-Benz, with about 290,000 employees at home and 67,200
abroad, consists of Mercedes-Benz, Daimler-Benz Aerospace and
Daimler-Benz Interservices (DEBIS). 
</P>
</TEXT>
