<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Car Sales down in W. Europe in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- New car sales in western Europe
fell by three percent in March compared with the same month last
year, according to figures released by the European Automobile
Manufacturers Association (EAMA) today.
</P>
<P>
The EAMA said that new car sales last month in France dropped
sharply, down 21.1 percent, while sales in Germany, Europe's
biggest car market, was also weak, down 8.6 percent on last year.
</P>
<P>
It linked the sharp fall in sales to the effect of ending
government and industry incentive schemes this year, which it
believed distorted demand last year and pulled sales forward in
the above two countries.
</P>
<P>
Although sales in Italy soared by 25.1 percent last month also
due to the Italian government's incentive scheme introduced in
January, this was easily overshadowed by the decline in France and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that total sales in western Europe would have
dropped by a more dramatic 6.4 percent in March had sales in Italy
remained at last year's level.
</P>
<P>
The situation was also clearly shown in manufacturers'
performance. Fiat's group sales rose by 7.5 percent last month on
the back of sharply higher Italian sales while Renault fell by 8.9
percent and Peugeot-Citroen by 7.4 percent as home market demand
fell.
</P>
<P>
Figures showed that South Korean brands, which enjoyed
virtually constant rises in the past two years, also recorded a
surprise downturn last month, with sales falling by 9.2 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
