<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Boost Telephone Communication, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will increase
the number of telephone lines in the next six years to six
million -- doubling the present three million, a top official
said today.
</P>
<P>
Two million of these would go to rural areas, squatter camps and
townships, South African Posts and Telecommunications Minister Jay
Naidoo told the parliament, adding that one million analogue
lines would be replaced by digital lines.
</P>
<P>
Naidoo said 24,000 priority customers -- such as schools and
clinics-- had been identified and the costs of the first line would
be borne by Telkom, a major telephone enterprise in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said over the next five years, an additional 125,000 public
telephones would be installed, bringing South Africa to above the
average of other middle-income countries -- approximately five public
telephones per thousand people in the rural areas and 3.5 per thousand
in the urban areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to financial support to the great telecommunication
project, the minister expressed that the department concerned would
make full use of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
The sale of 30 percent of Telkom's equity to a consortium of
Malaysian counterpart and South-Western Bell International has brought
5.5 billion Rands (1.25 billion U.S. dollars), the biggest foreign
investment in frastructure in South Africa since 1994, he said.
enditem

