<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inequality Increases Greatly in UK Since 1979: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Policies adopted by the
government, such as cuts in taxes and benefits and growing pay
differentials, have widened social divisions and increased
inequality in Britain since 1979, according to a report published
today.
</P>
<P>
The report by the charity Child Poverty Action Group pointed
out that between 1979 and 1994 the real income of the bottom 10
percent of the population fell by 13 percent while the average
rose 40 percent and the income of the top-ten soared by 65
percent.
</P>
<P>
It said that during the same period, the population living in
poverty, defined as below 50 percent of average income after
housing costs, rose from nine percent to 25 percent, a rise from
five million people to 13.7 million.
</P>
<P>
Britain's rise in inequality was matched only by New Zealand
among the developed countries of the world, the report added.
</P>
<P>
Alan Walker, professor of social policy at the University of
Sheffield, said in the introduction of the report that while the
rise was an international trend, Britain's extreme case was
largely due to the government having "purposely pursued policies
which widened social divisions in British society".
</P>
<P>
The study pointed out that economic inequality in Britain has
grown across a wide range of fields ranging from access to quality
education and health-care to the provision of adequate housing.
</P>
<P>
This is due to a combination of factors including demographic
shifts, tax cuts for the wealthy and a growing number of low-paid
jobs.
</P>
<P>
Sally Witcher, director of the charity, said that the study
showed a desperate need for the growing divide between rich and
poor to be bridged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
