<HEADLINE> U.S. Industrial Production Grows in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. industrial production
picked up 0.9 percent in March, according to a report from the
Federal Reserve here today.
</P>
<P>
The growth, nearly double what economists expected, brought the
industrial operating rate to 84.1 percent, up from 83.6 percent in
February and the highest level in two years, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Some economists believe that an operating rate of around 85
percent is a sign of inflation-producing strains in the production
pipeline.
</P>
<P>
Today's report is also regarded as bad news for Wall Street
investors and others worried that inflation pressures will cause
the Federal Reserve to continue raising interest rates through the
summer in a bid to control inflation.
</P>
<P>
Bond prices, which had surged Tuesday, slipped this morning
after the housing construction figures were released. Yields on
30-year Treasury bonds, which move in the opposite direction of
prices, went up to 7.10 percent in early trading from 7.09 percent
late yesterday. 
</P>
