<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Arrived in Germany for Talks with Kohl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian president Boris Yeltsin
arrived in Germany this afternoon for a two-day stay in the
country's famous spa town Baden-Baden on the edge of the Black
Forest, where he was to met with German Chancellor Helmut Kohl on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin arrived at the Stuttgart airport in the company of his
wife Naina and daughter-adviser Tatjana. Since his operation, this
was Yeltsin's second foreign trip. Last month, he held talks with
US president Bill Clinton in Helsinki.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin's meeting with Kohl, initially planned as a ceremony
for him to receive a media prize, was the 20th such since he
became Russian president in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Their talks are expected to focus on Moscow's continued
rejection of eastwards expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) and the German demand for return of art
treasures seized by the former Soviet Union in 1945.
</P>
<P>
Russia demanded firm guarantees that NATO will not extend its
military infrastructure up to its border. NATO noted it was not
willing to make such guarantee though it saw no need to deploy new
forces in Central Europe in the absence of a military threat.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations on a NATO-Russia charter in bid to mollify
Moscow over NATO enlargement have thus reached a crucial stage.
Kohl is expected to determine from Thursday talks whether Moscow
means the demand, or only makes it a bargaining ploy before the
hoped-for signing of the charter on May 27.
</P>
<P>
During the Thursday talks, Yeltsin and Kohl would also discuss
the fate of about one million German art treasures, two million
rare books and ancient archives which Bonn said was seized by the
former Soviet Union in 1945 from the defeated Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin supported returning the art treasures, but was blocked
by the Russian parliament Duma, which, just two weeks ago,
overrode Yeltsin's latest veto of the legislation that would made
these works of art Russia's state property.
</P>
<P>
These pieces of art include paintings by Monet, Degas, Renoire,
El Greco, Goya, Rembrandt and Rubens. Among them was also the
legendary golden treasure from Troy, which was unearthed by German
archeologist Heinrich Schliemann.  
</P>
</TEXT>
