<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Electronic Giant Buys US Computer Maker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Samsung Electronics Company
of South Korea has decided to acquire AST Research Inc. a computer
maker which is based in Irvine, California of the United States,
according to a report of the New York Times today.
</P>
<P>
The 170 million U.S. dollar deal is aimed to revive a
once-popular brand name that AST had enjoyed but now is devalued.
</P>
<P>
Two years ago, Samsung, which is a unit of the Samsung Group of
South Korea, began investing in AST, which acquired reputation for
high quality and performance in 1980's. But the computer maker was
never able to adapt to the more competitive personal computer
market of 1990's. From June 1995 to December 1996, AST accumulated
operating losses of 608 million U.S. dollars. In such
circumstances, Samsung decided to acquire the U.S. computer maker
and sell personal computers under its own name.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that acquisition of the U.S. company reflects
strong long term approach of Samsung to the PC business in the
global markets, especially in the Asian rim countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
