<HEADLINE> EU-Med Conference Highlights Sense of Common </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VALLETTA, MALTA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The second
European-Mediterranean conference closed here today with the 27
participating countries stressing the need of common interests
among them in their cooperation process.
</P>
<P>
In his closing ceremony address, the Maltese Prime Minister
Alfred Sant said the success of the meeting is attributed to
all the countries' "genuine and vested interest in the
(Euro-Mediterranean) Partnership."
</P>
<P>
The meeting has taken place when the Middle East peace
process is at a "most critical and fragile phase."
</P>
<P>
The negative impact of the Middle East peace process on
the EU-Mediterranean cooperation was one of the hottest topics
at the conference.
</P>
<P>
The closing ceremony was delayed for five hours due to
the argument in the conference how the stability and security
issues, particularly the Middle East peace process, should be
put in the final document.
</P>
<P>
The draft document accused unilateral violation of signed
Middle East peace agreements, referring to Israeli hardline
policies.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the meeting, the participating countries
softened their tone by leaving out the hard terms, just
expressing concern and hoping for a lasting peace based on
signed agreements.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that substantial progress in their
cooperation has been achieved, despite the uncertainties of the
regional political and security situation.
</P>
<P>
The EU president Hans Van Mierlo, foreign minister of the
Netherlands, described the meeting as one of the "nicest that
has ever been held."
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after the conference, Mierlo said one
of the other major achievements at the conference is the
direct meeting of Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Yasser
Arafat and Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy today.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, brokered by the EU, was the first direct
official one between the two sides since the Middle East peace
process plunged to the worst crisis in its seven-year history.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Greece and Turkey have achieved
progress in finding solution to their territorial disputes over
Aegean islands, Mierlo said, but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The EU also initialed an association agreement with Jordan
in light of the EU-Mediterranean cooperation blueprint. This
brings the number of the countries having such accords with EU
up to eight.
</P>
<P>
Because of differencs, the final document could not be adopted
at the end of the conference, but the participants reviewed the
progress achieved during the European-Mediterranean cooperation
for the past 15 months.
</P>
<P>
The Malta conference, the second of this type, has also
reviewed the progress achieved in the Euro-Mediterranean cooperation
which was launched in the first Barcelona conference in November
1995, and find practical ways to push it ahead.
</P>
<P>
The Barcelona conference set up a goal to establish an EU-Med
free-trade zone by 2010 through forging partnership with Algeria,
Cyprus, Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Malta, Morocco, Syria,
Tunisia, Turkey and Palestine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
