<HEADLINE> First Batch of Turkish Troops Leaves for Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The first convoy of Turkish
troops today left the Aegean city of Izmir for Albania to join a
multinational protection force to maintain security there, a
military statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement issued by Turkey's General Staff said that a
153-strong Turkish force and six vehicles went to Tirana,
capital of Albania, by air to take part in the "Mission Alba"
organized by the United Nations in a bid to protect the security
of Tirana Airport.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, the second batch of a 246-strong
force together with four military ships will leave Sunday for
Albania by sea and the last convoy of a 280-strong force will
fly from Izmir to Tirana on April 24.
</P>
<P>
Turkish military sources said that Turkey would be
responsible for Tirana, the Tirana Airport and the northern part
of Albania and the Turkish contingent is commanded by Marine
Colonel Suleyman Bozkurt with troops selected from
specially-trained marine and commandos of the Turkish navy.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News said today that Turkey also
plans to send cargo aircraft three times a month to Albania in
an effort to provide continuous logistic support for its
contingent there.
</P>
<P>
Turkey recently established a satellite communication
center near the Tirana Airport to further improve its electronic
capabilities in that country, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
During the telephone conversations between Turkish President
Suleyman Demirel and his Albanian counterpart Sali Berisha
Tuesday evening, Demirel stressed that Turkey would always extend
its friendly hand to Albania and would continue to provide
support for the country.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish government has also decided to provide a
50-million-dollar aid to help Albania overcome its
difficulties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
