<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: UN Steps Up Efforts to Solve Cyprus Problem (I) (by Huang Jianming) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. has stepped up efforts
to solve the long-standing Cyprus problem through an intensifed
mediation by a U.N. special envoy.
</P>
<P>
Han Sung Joo, the special envoy, left here today after his
four-day mission in Cyprus to foster the ongoing peace process on
the island.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, he had separate meetings with Cypriot
President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash, but the U.N. official refrained from giving details on
the U.N.-led proximity talks between the Greek and Turkish
Cypriot sides, which will pave the way for direct negotiations.
</P>
<P>
During his outgoing visit, Han brought here a surprising news
that he will step down from his post at the end of his term in
office on April 30, because of his "other responsibilities" and
"difficulties" that impede his task.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed as U.N. Secretary-General's Special
Representative for Cyprus to replace former Canadian Prime
Minister Joe Clark in May last year.
</P>
<P>
However, diplomatic sources here noted that Han's resignation
will not affect the ongoing U.N.-led peace process in Cyprus,
which is gaining momentum after U.N. Chief Kofi Annan met with
Turkish Cypriot leader Denktash in Geneva last week.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Annan underlined to Denktash the need to
move forward on the Cyprus problem and to work toward an overall
settlement. The U.N. Chief looks forward that face-to-face
negotiations between President Glafcos Clerides and Denktash will
begin by mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Denktash called on President Clerides to join
him in direct talks, noting that the parameters for the
settlement of the Cyprus problem are on the table, known as the
Set of Ideas proposed by former U.N. Chief Boutros
Boutros-Ghali.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot leader expressed the hope that the
U.N. secretary general will find ways and means to bring both
sides to the negotiation table, which he hopes to take place in
the middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Annan-Denktash meeting took place after the U.N.-sponsored
proximity talks between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides
entered the fifth week, during which U.N. Resident Representative
Gustave Feissel had bi-weekly separate meetings with President
Clerides and Denktash in a bid to prepare the ground for
face-to-face negotiations, and to get the two sides to
unilaterally adopt good-will gestures.
</P>
<P>
Nothing concrete has been revealed since the talks began on
March 10, because the parties involved have committed themselves
to an agreement not to publish the content of the talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: UN Steps Up Efforts to Solve Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, Feissel disclosed that some progress has been made in
the proximity talks on both the substance of the Cyprus problem
and the mutual good-will gestures aimed at fostering a positive
climate for direct negotiations, although the U.N. official
declined to go into details.
</P>
<P>
Outgoing U.N. envoy Han Sung Joo said after meetings with
President Clerides and Denktash Monday that there is now more
hope to get the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides around the
negotiating table than in the past.
</P>
<P>
It seems that the Turkish Cypriot leader Denktash is
optimistic. He was quoted as saying that the direct meeting
planned for June can take place if there is progress on the
Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
On the part of the Greek Cypriot side, Government Spokesman
Manolis Christofides has said it is too early to determine
whether there is sufficient common ground between the views of
the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides to enable direct
negotiations for an overall settlement in Cyprus to begin.
</P>
<P>
He also indicated that the governments of Cyprus and Greece
together with the National Council, the top advisory body to
President Clerides on handling the Cyprus problem, will assess
the outcome of the proximity talks and decide whether the
conditions for direct talks have been met.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the U.N.-sponsored indirect military
dialogue between Cypriot armed force, the National Guard, and
Turkish forces on the island is still going on, according to the
U.N. sources.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which began last year, were aimed at reaching an
agreement on the package submitted by the U.N. in order to reduce
tension along the 180-kilometer buffer zone. The package includes
unmanning of the areas where the two sides are at close proximity
with each other, the prohibition of located weapons along the
cease-fire line and the code of conduct for the military along
the cease-fire line.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus problem has remained unsolved for the past 23 years
since the island was divided after Turkish troops landed and
seized the northern third of the island in 1974.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored peace talks aimed at reuniting the island
under a bizonal and bicommunal federal state, have been held on
and off, but so far no tangible results have been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash have not met since October 1994 when
the two men held two rounds of informal talks in Nicosia under
the U.N. auspices.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that if the U.N. proposed direct
negotiations between the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides can be
held by the middle of this year, it will be a major step toward
an overall settlement to the protracted Cyprus question. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
