<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Urges Afghan Parties to Cease Hostilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The UN Security Council
today called upon the Afghan parties to cease immediately all
hostile actions and to enter into sustained negotiations,
according to a presidential statement adopted by the council
today.
</P>
<P>
"The council strongly believes that a negotiated settlement is
the only solution to the long-standing conflict in this country,"
said the statement of Antonio Monteiro, Portuguese ambassador and
council president for April.
</P>
<P>
Expressing its full support for the United Nations efforts to
facilitate national reconciliation in Afghanistan, the Security
Council was convinced that the United Nations must continue to
play the central role in assisting the warring Afghan factions to
engage in a fully-fledged negotiating process on the basis of the
Security Council resolution 1076 and General Assembly resolution
51/195.
</P>
<P>
As many important provisions of the resolutions above remained
unimplemented, the council called upon all Afghan parties, in
particular the Taliban, to abide by these resolutions, to
cooperate fully with the United Nations Special Mission in
Afghanistan (UNSMA) and to participate in serious and honest
negotiations through the good offices of the UNSMA.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council also called upon all states to end
immediately the supply of arms and ammunition to all parties to
the conflict in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the council expressed its deep concern at the
worsening of the humanitarian situation, and discrimination
against women and other violations of human rights and of
international humanitarian law in Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
