<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Police Recommend Indicting Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In another dramatic revelation, Channel I crime reporter
Ayala Hasson, who first broke the news about the so-called
"Bar-On for Hebron" scandal that sparked the three-month police
investigation, said police investigators had recommended
indictments of breach of trust against Netanyahu, Justice
Minister Tzahi Hanegbi, Prime Minister's Office Director-General
Avigdor Liberman and religious Shas party leader Areyh
Deri.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that the police only recommended
indictments against Deri for blackmailing, and Hanegbi and
Liberman for breach of trust. The indictment against Netanyahu
is expected to have dramatic implications on the current
government, because any government official charged with breach
of trust is likely forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
The police investigation team presented Tuesday the probe
findings and recommendations to State Attorney Edana Arbel, who
will decide whether to adopt them within the next few days after
consultations with current Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein.
</P>
<P>
According to Hasson's report, Shas leader Deri had pushed for
the appointment of former Jerusalem lawyer Roni Bar-On because
the latter promised him a plea-bargain in his three-year long
bribery and fraud trial. Shas is the third largest party in
Israel and has been an indispensable ruling partner either for
the Labor or Likud, the two leading parties.
</P>
<P>
Deri reportedly conditioned Shas' support of the Hebron
agreement on Bar-On's appointment. Liberman was said to have
played a middle-man between Deri and the government over
appointing Bar-On, who ironically resigned automatically two days
after the January 10 appointment under the pressure over his
politicial affiliation and insufficient qualifications.
</P>
<P>
If indictments are indeed filed, the Netanyahu government
will come under heavy pressure to resign or undergo a major
resuffle. But even no indictment was filed, the scandal has
already inflicted damage to the image of the Likud government.
</P>
<P>
Hasson said that even a failure to indict because of
infufficient evidence was tantamount to guilt of the government,
which could be forced to resign under the pressure of the public
opinion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
