<HEADLINE> PM: Lebanon to Continue Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri vowed here today that his government will continue its
program of building and reconstructing the state despite the
"very very difficult" situation in the Middle East region.
</P>
<P>
Hariri, who returned home today from a trip to Russia, Canada
and France, discussed domestic issues and regional situation with
Lebanese president Elias Hrawi and House Speaker Nabih Berri.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters in the Presidential Palace after the
meeting, Hariri said "there is no doubt that the peace process is
still in a very very difficult phase."
</P>
<P>
"The situation will remain as it is," the premier said, "we
the Lebanese have repeatedly said that we believe in the peace
but we do not bet on it."
</P>
<P>
"We will complete our program, the building of the state will
continue, our relations with the friendly countries will
continue, the plans of reconstruction and development will
continue," Hariri announced.
</P>
<P>
"We will handle the problem of south Lebanon within this
framework, " Hariri added.
</P>
<P>
He said that he and the Russian, Canadian and French leaders
unanimously agreed that "the peace process is passing through a
serious crisis and Israel is responsible for it."
</P>
<P>
On a proposed "security pact" among the Middle East
countries, the prime minister admitted that he discussed this
issue with French President Jacques Chirac during their meeting
in Paris Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The security issue was raised in the Euro-Mediterranean
conference in Barcelona, Spain, in November 1995. Hariri said that
the Arab position was that it was "premature" to talk about an
accord on this problem "before a just and comprehensive peace was
reached with Israel." 
</P>
</TEXT>
