<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Closed-door Talks between
South African President Nelson Mandela and Zairean rebel leader
Laurent Kabila lasted only 45 minutes in Cape Town today, said a
source reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, aimed at finding a political solution to war in
Zaire and having been expected to last well into the night, has
"broken up," said Presidential spokesman Parks Mankahlana. He
declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said Mandela "was positive about the
discussions" with Kabila.
</P>
<P>
Mandela might have tried at the meeting to convince Kabila to
agree to a ceasefire and a meeting with Zairean President Mobutu
Sese Seko, whom Kabila had reportedly refused to meet, according
to the source.
</P>
<P>
Kabila would return to Lumbumbashi, Zaire's second largest
city on Thursday morning, it added.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time Mandela and Kabila have met in South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Kabila, the leader of the Alliance of Democratic Forces for
the Liberation of Congo-Zaire, arrived in Cape Town earlier
today. 
