<HEADLINE> Hussein Expresses Sympathy for Victims of Mecca </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 16 (Xinhua) - King of Jordan Hussein today sent a
cable to king Fahd of Saudi Arabia to express his sympathy to the
victims of a fire that swept through the tent camps of Muslim
pilgrims near Mecca Tuesday, Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
In the cable, the King also praised the Saudi Arabian
authority for its efforts to deal with the incident that
killed 217 people and wounded 1,300 others.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government Tuesday said that there were
no Jordanian casualties among the pilgrims who were camped north
of Mina when a gas cylinder explosion nearby caused a fire
that tore through the encampment.
</P>
<P>
A senior Jordanian official said that all Jordanians at the
camp were in excellent conditions and that no one was hurt in the
fire.
</P>
<P>
Some two million Muslims are participating in the pilgrimage
this year.
</P>
<P>
The Hajj pilgrimage attracts the world's largest number of
people at any one time, and security is always a priority in the
country. Tension in Saudi Arabia has been high following a major
bombing in 1995 that killed a number of U.S. servicemen.
</P>
<P>
In Saudi Arabia in 1994, 270 pilgrims died in a stampede. In
1990, 1,426 people were crushed to death in a tunnel leading to a
holy site in that country. In 1987, a rally by Iranian pilgrims
led to clashes with Saudi security forces there, in which 402
pilgrims, mostly Iranians, were Killed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
