<HEADLINE> Somali Faction Leader Rejects Foreign Interference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Somali faction leader Hussein
Farah Aideed said here today he welcomes Arab efforts to mediate
an end to the Somali conflicts but rejects foreign interference,
the Egyptian MENA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Aideed, before wrapping up his week-long visit to Egypt
Thursday, reiterated the importance of Egypt's role in settling
the Somali problem and urged the Arab League (AL) and the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) to reinforce their efforts.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he cautioned against "some outside and inside
foreign intervention" in the six-year warring conflict in the
Horn of African country, referring partly to the mounting tension
on its border with Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
"I believes that the Somali problems should be resolved by the
Somalis themselves, if they are sincere in serving their
country," said the Somalia National Alliance leader.
</P>
<P>
"The conferences administered by foreign powers can never be
an alternative to a national one," he added, referring to some
foreign intervention in Somali internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Aideed said he is ready to have constructive talks with his
compatriotic counterparts, adding that there are 16 instead of 27
internationally recognized factions in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
"The interim government is working to mobilize the popular
leaderships in Somalia that contains of 18 provinces...I am ready
to negotiate with any major force that has influence in this
African state," he added.
</P>
<P>
Denying that he refused to take part in any reconciliation
conference, Aideed said, however, that he would not attend the
conferences that are of no significance.
</P>
<P>
In the latest of a string of Arab consultations with various
Somali factions, AL chief Esmat Abdu1-Meguid and Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak Monday held talks with Aideed on
rebuilding Somalia and the reconciliation process initiated by
the transitional government since March.
</P>
<P>
Aideed, leader of the most powerful militia in the southern
half of the Somali capital, Mogadishu, arrived here Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
