<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peres Demands Netanyahu's Resignation over Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Israeli opposition Labor's
leader Shimon Peres demanded today Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu resign immediately following the revelation that police
recommended indicting Netanyahu for his involvement in a
political scandal.
</P>
<P>
In this evening's news program, the state-run Television
Channel I revealed the police investigators probing the "Bar-On
for Hebron" scandal were recommending indicting Netanyahu for
breach of trust and fraud in appointing the attorney-general in
January. This had dropped a political bombshell to the Jewish
state.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the report in an interview with Channel I,
Peres said if the report was true, then it amounted to be an
"earthquake" in the Jewish state. He demanded Netanyahu step
down immediately and call for new elections.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Peres announced that he no longer pushed for
the formation of a national unity government with the
Netanyahu-led Likud party. He also said that he would make severe
criticism of the Netanyahu government over its mismanagement in
the Bar-On scandal.
</P>
<P>
Peres' latest statements signaled a dramatic turnaround in
his attitude toward the government since he held secret talks only
last week with Netanyahu to discuss forming a unity government,
despite other senior Labor members' strong opposition. Following
the scandal probe, the Labor is expected to intensify its
campaign to bring down the Likud government.
</P>
<P>
Following the Channel I's revelation about the police
recommendations of indictment against Netanyahu, government
spokesman Shai Bazak denied the report. He said that
the final decision should be made by State Attorney Edana Arbel
and current Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein, who will make a
formal decision on the indictments within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
But Public Security Minister Avigdor Kahalani confirmed that
it was true that the police investigators had recommended
indicting Netanyahu for breach of trust and fraud. He said earlier
that the government should step down if any minister could be
charged for involvement in the Bar-On scandal.
</P>
<P>
According to Channel I reporter Ayala Hasson, who first
broke the news about the so-called "Bar-On for Hebron" scandal
that sparked the three-month police investigation, police
investigators were recommending indictments of breach of trust
against Netanyahu, Justice Minister Tzahi Hanegbi, Prime
Minister's Office Director-General Avigdor Liberman. Charges
against religious Shas party leader Areyh Deri would be
blackmailing, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said the police only recommended indictments
against Deri, Hanegbi and Liberman. The police investigation
team presented Tuesday the probe findings and recommendations to
State Attorney Arbel and Attorney-General Rubinstein.
</P>
<P>
According to Hasson's report, Shas leader Deri had pushed for
the appointment of former Jerusalem lawyer Roni Bar-On because
the latter promised him a plea-bargain in his three-year long
bribery and fraud trial.
</P>
<P>
Deri reportedly conditioned Shas' support of the Hebron
agreement with the Palestinians on Bar-On's appointment. Liberman
was said to have acted as the middle-man between Deri and the
government over appointing Bar-On, who ironically resigned two
days after the January 10 appointment under the pressure over his
political affiliation and insufficient qualifications.
</P>
<P>
If any indictment is indeed filed against Netanyahu, the
10-month old Likud government will likely be forced to resign to
pave the way for new elections. Health Minister Yehoshua Matza
told Israel Radio that he thought that the only possibility will
be calling for new elections if charges against Netanyahu would
be filed.
</P>
<P>
Even if no indictment is filed, the scandal has already
inflicted damage to the image of the government, which is
expected to undergo a major reshuffle.
</P>
<P>
Hasson said even a failure to indict because of insufficient
evidence was tantamount to guilt of the government, which could
be forced to resign under the pressure of the public
opinion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
