<HEADLINE> France Denounces Zairian Rebels for Refusing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- France denounced this evening
Zairian rebels led by Laurent-Desire Kabila for refusing to
seriously hold talks with the Zairian government, and warned the
rebels that their conquest of power by arms would only lead the
country into "indefinable chaos."
</P>
<P>
The French denouncement came after a Zairian rebel spokesman
said in Goma today that the rebels would not agree to a cease-fire
because a cease-fire would benefit the Zairian government and let
it win time.
</P>
<P>
"All other ways (for a solution), and especially the conquest
of power by arms, will bring Zaire into an indefinable chaos,"
said the French Foreign Ministry in a communique.
</P>
<P>
In a clear reference to the rebels, the communique said, "Those
who would persist in this way, or who would accept it, would take
a very heavy responsibility for Zaire and the whole region."
</P>
<P>
It said that France is deeply worried about the "dangerous and
unacceptable situation in Zaire," and denounces "the refusal of
any real negotiation for an orderly transition which will allow
this country (Zaire)... to go out of the present impasse and build
a future."
</P>
<P>
France has repeatedly called on the Zairian rebels and the
Zairian government to hold talks to prepare for a transitional
period in Zaire before organizing elections.
</P>
<P>
The rebels have recently scored a number of victories in
fighting against the government forces by conquering the southern
mineral rich province of Shaba and part of the south-central
regions, and are controlling half of the country's territory.
</P>
<P>
Kabila is now asking Zairian President Mobutu Sese Seko to step
down first before a cease-fire can be arranged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
