<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Propose New Campaign Finance Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- A group of Democrats in the
U.S. House of Representatives today proposed a campaign finance
reform bill aimed at overturning a Supreme Court decision
forbidding campaign spending limits.
</P>
<P>
The bill will establish general spending limits, ban so-called
soft money, and require the total disclosure of the source of
every dollar raised.
</P>
<P>
Representative Jane Harman, Democrat of California, said the
"chief obstacle to campaign reform" is a 1976 Supreme Court
decision, Buckley vs. Valeo, that forbid campaign spending limits.
</P>
<P>
Group members contended the 1976 decision, in rejecting overall
spending limits but allowing the regulation of contributions, has
left candidates in a desperate search for money.
</P>
<P>
They said the Supreme Court, given its 1996 decision in the
Colorado Republican Campaign Committee vs. the Federal Election
Commission, has indicated it would allow spending limits if given
a new test case.
</P>
<P>
One of the most prominent campaign finance reform bills,
sponsored by Sens. John McCain, Republican of Arizona, and Russ
Feingold, Democrat from Wisconsin, has the backing of President
Bill Clinton but found few supporters among Republicans.
</P>
<P>
The McCain-Feingold bill also will ban "soft money." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
