<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-16 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peres Suspends Push for Unity Government Following </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The hope for forming a
unity government in Israel was dashed today when opposition
Labor's leader Shimon Peres decided to suspend his efforts
following a police investigation into a corruption scandal of
the current government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking this afternoon upon his return from a tour of
South America, Peres said he would not continue his efforts
to join a unity government with the ruling Likud party.
</P>
<P>
The former premier made the decision amid reports that the
police investigation into the so-called "Bar-On for Hebron"
scandal had uncovered serious corruption surrounding the abortive
appointment of Jerusalem lawyer Roni Bar-On as the
attorney general in January.
</P>
<P>
Police investigators presented all findings and recommendations
to the State Attorney's Office Tuesday after the three-month
probe, in which about 60 people were questioned, including
Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu, Justice Minister Tzahi Hanegbi,
Prime Minister's Office Director-General Avigdor Liberman and the
religious Shas party leader Areyh Deri.
</P>
<P>
The "Bar-On for Hebron" scandal was exposed by state-run
Television Channel I crime reporter Ayala Hasson, who revealed
that Shas leader Deri had pushed for the appointment of
Bar-On because the latter promised him a plea bargain in his
three-year bribery and fraud trial.
</P>
<P>
Deri reportedly conditioned Shas' support of the Hebron
agreement on Bar-On's appointment. Liberman was said to have
played a middle-man between Deri and the government over
appointing Bar-On, who ironically resigned two days
after appointment under the pressure due to his political
affiliation and insufficient qualifications.
</P>
<P>
Although the police findings have yet been publicized, local
media exposed that police investigators had recommended the
State Attorney's Office charge Deri with blackmailing, and
Hanegbi and Liberman with breach of trust.
</P>
<P>
If the indictments are indeed filed, the Likud government will
come under heavy pressure from the opposition and public to
resign or undergo a major reshuffle. But even no indictment
was filed, the scandal has already inflicted damage to the
image of the Likud government.
</P>
<P>
In view of the findings of the corruption investigation,
Peres has finally changed his mind on pushing for a unity
government in order to rescue the derailed peace process which
he pioneered. Last week, Peres reportedly held secret
discussions with Netanyahu over the prospects of forming a
unity government in order to advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
However, Labor's new generation leaders strongly oppose the
idea of joining a unity government with the Likud, especially
following the police investigation into the Bar-On affair.
Instead, they favor strengthening its campaign to topple the
Likud government and call for new elections.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has been flirting with the idea of unity
government for a long time without making an official
decision. Faced with the current crisis in the peace process
and the difficulty of proceeding forward due to the strong
opposition from ultra-rightist forces within the coalition,
Netanyahu is believed to be seriously considering the option
of forming a unity government with the Labor Party.
</P>
<P>
Later today, Netanyahu will meet with Shas' spiritual leader
Ovadia Yosef to discuss the issue of unity government. Shas, the
third largest party in Israel, has been an indispensable ruling
partner either for the Labor or Likud party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
