<HEADLINE> Teachers in Angola's Luanda Province Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Primary school teachers in
Angola's Luanda Province decided here today to continue their
strike launched one month ago until the government meets their
demands.
</P>
<P>
The trade union of teachers in the province, when making the
decision, said it is still willing to negotiate with Education
Minister Antonio Burity on how to solve the troubles the teachers
face.
</P>
<P>
The teachers demand the government pay their long-term unpaid
wages, set their lowest wage level at about 250 U.S. Dollars and
approve an agenda of teaching as a special profession.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Antonio criticized the teachers strike in his speech
to reporters, describing the strike as disobedience.
</P>
<P>
Since their wages have been behind in payment for a long time,
the teachers in the region often hold strikes.
</P>
<P>
The newly-stalled Angolan government of national unity and
reconciliation claimed Tuesday that it is one of the government's
priorities to solve the problems in the education circle.
</P>
