<HEADLINE> US Dollar Weakens Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar ended mostly
higher but fell against the yen today after Japan's top currency
policy-maker said the yen is too weak and the senior U.S. trade
negotiator warned Japan to curb its growing surplus.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the dollar settled at 125.75 yen, down from 126.09
yen Tuesday. The dollar cost 1.7283 marks, up from 1.7270. The
pound cost 1.6244 U.S. dollars, down from 1.6316 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that despite the dollar's retreat against the
yen, the basic forces pushing the dollar higher against the yen
remain in place -- higher interest rates in the U.S. and low
interest rates in Japan, which have attracted Japanese investment
flows into the United States.
</P>
<P>
The dollar also derived some strength from the fact that the
dollar and the pound in recent months reflect a correction from
earlier weakness and favorable economic conditions in the United
States and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Other late dollar rates in New York compared with Tuesday:
1.4715 Swiss francs, up from 1.4665; 5.8105 French francs, up from
5.8085; 1,701.00 Italian lire, up from 1,699.25; 1.3966 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.3965. 
</P>
</TEXT>
