<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Freedoms to Be Preserved: Chief Executive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) is determined that Hong Kong's way
of life and the many freedoms that Hong Kong people now enjoy will
continue unchanged in the future, Tung Chee Hwa, HKSAR Chief
Executive, said here today.
</P>
<P>
Officiating at the Prize Presentation Ceremony of the Hong Kong
Best Press Articles and Photographs of the Year Awards 1996, Tung
said that Hong Kong has enjoyed remarkable social stability, which
has been fundamental to the economic success of the territory over
the years.
</P>
<P>
"Stability is indeed the bedrock of prosperity. Having had
both (social stability and economic success) for a very long time,
it is easy to forget that, being a small and open economy, Hong
Kong is extremely vulnerable to external forces," he said.
</P>
<P>
"As a community, we must ensure that there are sufficient
safeguards in our system to maintain law and order at all times,
and to react to unforeseen circumstances swiftly and effectively."
</P>
<P>
He said the HKSAR Office's proposals in the consultation
document on amendments to the Societies Ordinance and the Public
Order Ordinance were in compliance with the Basic Law and the
United Nations International Covenant on Civil and Political
Rights (ICCPR).
</P>
<P>
He said the amendments to the two Ordinances, necessary to
avoid any legal vacuum arising on July 1, were not aimed at any
particular individuals, groups or organizations, adding that the
objective was to find a point of balance between individual rights
and social order.
</P>
<P>
On the amendments for the Societies Ordinance, he said, "In the
interest of six million Hong Kong people I think we cannot allow
foreign interference with Hong Kong's political development.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, nearly every Government in the world has some kind of
legislation or another to prohibit foreign interference in
domestic affairs," he said.
</P>
<P>
Based on this broad principle, proposals were devised to
prohibit political organizations in Hong Kong from establishing
ties with those in foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the Public Order Ordinance, Tung said that the
consideration was for every citizen to enjoy the highest degree of
rights and freedoms while maintaining basic public order.
</P>
<P>
"The key question here for the community to debate is: What is
more important to the community: social order or rights of the
individual?" Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that in the interests of the community as a whole,
appropriate management of demonstrations is to find the right
point of balance between the rights of the individual and social
order," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We must ensure that peaceful and lawful demonstrations can
continue. I see public demonstrations as a way for people to
express their views and now public demonstrations are a part of
Hong Kong's culture," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said many Western countries would not give up control over
public order and the majority of cities in North America,
including Washington, New York, Vancouver and Toronto, have permit
systems for demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
Noting that concerns had been expressed about the introduction
of the concept of "national security" without a comprehensive
explanation, Tung pointed out that the term existed in the Bill of
Rights Ordinance Sections 17 and 18.
</P>
<P>
"This term, along with others in the same section, is exactly
the same as those contained in Articles 21 and 22 of the ICCPR.
Therefore this is not a brand new concept to Hong Kong," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
