<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bildt Calls for Preventing Resort to Arms in Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SARAJEVO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Carl Bildt, the High
Representative in charge of Dayton accords implementation,
recommends that three course of actions, namely attempt to use
force, secession and ethnic domination, should be blocked in order
to stablize the Bosnian peace process.
</P>
<P>
The recommendation came in a report that Bildt will send to UN
security council late this month, Colum Murphy, spokesman for
Bildt said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
While the presence of Nato-led peace-keeping prevents any of
the ethnic groups from pursuing military means, it is the opinion
of the High Representative that the message should be sent that
international community will not tolerate any attempt to resort to
military force in the period after Nato troops pull out, Murphy
said.
</P>
<P>
Murphy said that there was a "creeping secession" as
demonstrated by Bosnian Serbs and Croats in forging "parallel
relations" with neighboring countries, while the tendency of
ethnic domination was still shown by Muslims who had not
dismantled the old state structures as required by the Dayton
peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Murphy quoted Bildt as saying that the continued political
influence wielded by persons indicted for war crimes in the
Republica Srpska "taints the personalities and institutions" of
the Serb entity.
</P>
<P>
Because of his tolerance of Radovan Karadzic, the former Serb
leader indicted for war crimes by an international court in the
Hague, the international organizations should limit their contacts
with Momcilo Krajisnik "to the essential business related to his
function as a member of the presidency," Bildt said in his report.
</P>
<P>
Bildt also recommended that except for humanitarian aid or for
election purpose, international assistance be cut off to the Serb
municipalities of Bosanski Samac and Foca where war crime
indictees continue to hold public office or exercise de facto
influence.
</P>
<P>
In his latest report, Bildt "regrets to say that he sees no
fundamental change" in stopping the trend towards ethnic
separation, since any attempt of large-scale return of refugees
has met with "fierce resistance ranging from violent to
bureaucratic".
</P>
<P>
But the report stressed the importance of economic recovery as
conditions for return of refugees, Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
"We can not expect refugees to return easily, if they see a
country in economic and social despair, so the two in our view are
very closely linked," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
