<HEADLINE> Taiwan Hijacker to be Repatriated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Liu Shan-chung, the Taiwanese who
hijacked a Far Eastern Airlines plane from Taiwan to Xiamen on
March 10, will be repatriated to Taiwan soon according to the
"Quemoy Agreement."
</P>
<P>
Sources came from the Association for Relations across the
Taiwan Straits (ARATS) and the Red Cross Society of China here
today.
</P>
<P>
The ARATS informed the Taiwan-based Straits Exchange Foundation
of this decision by letter this morning.
</P>
<P>
The letter said that the relevant department has finished
necessary investigations of hijacker Liu Shan-chung in the
hijacking incident on March 10. He will be repatriated according
to the "Quemoy Agreement."
</P>
<P>
"Specific matter related to the repatriation will be handled by
the Red Cross organizations across the Taiwan Straits," it said.
</P>
<P>
The letter also asked the Taiwan Straits Exchange Foundation to
tell the relevant side in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Qu Zhe, vice-president of the Red Cross Society of China, said
in his letter this morning to the Secretary-General of the Taiwan
Red Cross organization today that the Red Cross Society of the
Fujian Province will be responsible for liaison and witness of the
repatriation.
</P>
<P>
The letter expressed the hope that the Taiwan Red Cross will
coordinate with the relevant departments to do this work in a
proper way.
</P>
<P>
Since the "Quemoy Agreement" was singed in September, 1990, the
Red Cross organizations across the Taiwan Straits have become
involved in witnessing and repatriating 70 criminal suspects and
offenders including the forthcoming repatriation of Liu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
