<HEADLINE> Canada's Foreign Trade Gain Moderately in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A modest increase in exports
helped boost Canada's trade surplus to 1.6 billion dollars in
February from 1.4 billion in January, the country's statistics
agency said today.
</P>
<P>
But the trade surplus remained below its average level for 1996
after a sharp fall last October, Statistics Canada said. The
agency did not say how much the average surplus was in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Canada's exports in February rose by 0.6 percent to 17 billion
U.S. dollars after a 2.8 percent rise in January. More machinery
and forestry products were sold abroad in the month while most
other products witnessed a decrease, the federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
In February, the country imported 15.4 billion dollars, almost
the same as in January.
</P>
<P>
"A drop in energy product purchases was all but offset by
continued strength in industrial goods and consumer imports," the
agency said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
