<HEADLINE> China's Air Transport Expected to Have World's Highest Growth Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China's air transport is expected
to have the highest growth rate in the world, 10 percent annually,
over the next two decades, according to a recent report by Airbus
Industrie.
</P>
<P>
An Asia-Pacific market forecast by Airbus Industrie, one of the
world's leading aircraft manufacturers, shows that the number of
passengers in the Asia-Pacific region will have a year-on-year
growth of 6.4 percent on average from 1996-2016, while that for
the rest of the world market will be 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
By 2016, the total number of air passengers is expected to be
triple the 1996 figure.
</P>
<P>
The airline industry has been one of the fastest growing
sectors in China's economy since the country adopted its reform
and opening-up policies 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Air traffic averaged an annual increase of 16.3 percent from
1994 to 1996, according to the Civil Aviation Administration of
China (CAAC). Last year, Chinese airlines carried 55.51 million
passengers, and had an overall transport volume of 8.05 billion
ton-km.
</P>
<P>
CAAC is looking for annual growth of 13 percent for the airline
industry by 2000, with 80 million passengers, and a transport
volume of 12 billion ton-km.
</P>
<P>
China's rapidly growing air transport market has created many
opportunities for the world's aircraft manufacturers. To have a
fleet of 1,000 planes by the year 2000, the country has brought in
about 30 foreign-made planes each year, and this year is expecting
38 planes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
