<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irrigating Northwest China With Yarlung Water, Experts Propose (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A group of Chinese scientists
today suggested that China should divert water from southwest
China's Yarlung Zangbo River to irrigate arid northwest China 800
km away.
</P>
<P>
Chen Chuanyou, a well-known Chinese water resource expert, is
among the scientists who have advocated a plan to build a tunnel
for diverting water from the river to the northwestern part of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Yarlung Zangbo River, with a length of 2,057 km, is the river
with the biggest elevation in the world. It originates in
southwestern Tibet, travels eastwards through the Himalayas and
suddenly changes course southwards in southwestern Tibet, and then
flows out of China and eventually empties itself into the Bengal
Bay.
</P>
<P>
Chen explained that the program is aimed at digging a
30-km-long tunnel between Doxong and Medog at the sudden turn of
the river to better use its varying drops, and constructing a
hydropower station that will double the gigantic water
control-cum-hydro power station currently being built at the Three
Gorges on the middle reaches of the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
The station will also be used to divert 40 billion cu m of
water from the Yarlung Zangbo to irrigate the dry northwest China
and areas near the upper reaches of the Yellow River, Chen noted.
</P>
<P>
Northwest consists of Qinghai, Gansu, Shaanxi provinces and
Xinjiang Uygur and Ningxia Hui autonomous regions, whose combined
area accounts for a half of China's total area, and is the
country's major reserve area for resources and agricultural
development.
</P>
<P>
However, due to a severe shortage of water, the region has long
remained backward in social and economic development, with its
gross domestic product (GDP) only accounting for seven percent of
the country's total.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irrigating Northwest China With Yarlung Water, Experts Propose (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An official with the State Planning Commission said that if
this program is implemented, the exploitation of resources in
northwest China and in the areas of the upper reaches of the
Yellow River will be greatly accelerated.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, high-efficiency oasis farming will help China
solve food shortages in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Coupled with trees being planted in more areas of the Loess
Plateau, a new page will be opened for China to realize a
strategic change in shifting its economic development focus from
eastern coastal areas to the resource-rich western areas,
according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
The proposal has aroused wide attention in the scientific
community since it was raised three years ago. The Chinese Academy
of Sciences has organized several rounds of discussions among
experts; and the State Science and Technology Commission recently
decided to start feasibility research.
</P>
<P>
Relevant departments have also vowed to provide research and
prospecting with primary financial support, while the business
community has also shown a strong interest in getting involved in
this project.
</P>
<P>
Scientists of different fields, including many overseas
scientists, have also shown a strong interest in the proposal.
</P>
<P>
Wang Yunkai, a researcher with the Water Control and
Hydroelectrical Power Research Institute of the Ministry of Water
Resources, said the proposed design is superior to the
western-route plan to divert water from southern areas of China to
northern areas, which is now widely acclaimed, judging from
factors such as the volume of water flow, and the combination of
hydroelectrical generation and water diversion into one.
</P>
<P>
Wu Chuanjun, an academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences,
who is also an authority of geoeconomy in China, thought that the
plateau where the Yarlung Zangbo River is fed is a
sparsely-populated vast area and therefore, comparatively easier
to solve the resettlement work.
</P>
<P>
Wu also believed that the construction of a reservoir could
greatly improve the micro-climate of the river valley, and the
building of a large hydropower station will create favorable
conditions for the people of Tibet to make more money and become
prosperous.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese academician also said discharging water into the
river course during the dry season and storing water during flood
time is also an important measure to combat drought that plagues
northern Asia and to fight against floods occurring at the lower
reaches of the Yarlung Zangbo River -- Brahmaputra, Jamuna, and
the Ganges -- in India and Bangladesh before the river empties
into the Bengal Bay.
</P>
<P>
Geophysician Xu Zhonghuai said that it would cost a lot and
require the application of sophisticated technology to build such
a water diversion project on the "roof of the world".
</P>
<P>
Xu, also a researcher with the State Bureau of Seismology,
suggested that departments conduct on-the-spot prospecting into
areas where the proposed water diversion tunnel might pass through
quickly, to materialize the design as soon as possible. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
