<HEADLINE> Nepal to Administer Vitamin A to Children Under 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Nepal will administer vitamin A
capsules to some 1.4 million children across the country on Friday
and Saturday under a national health care program, the Health
Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
The vitamin A administration program, to be carried out in 32
of the country's 75 districts, is aimed at developing children's
mental faculty and immunity from eye diseases, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
About 17,000 women health workers have been mobilized for
administering the capsules to children aged between six months and
five years in the program areas.
</P>
<P>
According to the ministry, a study conducted in two Nepali
districts showed that child mortality rate dropped by 30 percent
after administering vitamin A pills to children in every six
months. 
</P>
