<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 14:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: 118 Iranians Die of Iraqi Chemical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A total of 118 Iranian war
veterans wounded by Iraqi chemical attacks during the eight-year
Iranian-Iraqi war (1980-88) have died since 1991, Iran's official
news agency IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that thousands of Iranian war victims are
suffering from severe injuries sustained from the Iraqi chemical
warfare during the war.
</P>
<P>
The victims of Iraqi chemical attacks, who are on the second
day of their sit-in protest in front of the German Embassy, vowed
to continue their demonstrations until their demands for actions
against German officials and firms supplying chemical warfare
weapons to Iraq were met.
</P>
<P>
Iran accused 24 German companies of supplying chemical
weapons and technology to Iraq during the war.
</P>
<P>
The victims also condemned the ruling of the Berlin court on
April 10, which accused the Iranian top leaders of involvement in
the political assassination of four Kurdish dissidents in Berlin
in 1992, and demanded an official German apology to Iran and to
Iranian officials.
</P>
<P>
Iran-Germany ties strained after the announcement of the
verdict of the Berlin court last Thursday which triggered off
widespread demonstration against Germany over the past week.
</P>
<P>
Hamid Sohrab-Pur, head of the Center for Victims of Chemical
Warfare, said that his center has so far obtained medical
records of 60,000 out of an estimated 100,000 chemically wounded
people.
</P>
<P>
At present, he said, 1,500 of such people living in various
parts of the country need constant medication.
</P>
<P>
He noted that those behind such crimes have been
identified and that the center holds a list of German companies
that supplied Iraq with chemical agents for use against Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said that his center has already cooperated with German
medical centers for treatment of Iranian chemically wounded
combatants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
