<HEADLINE> HKSAR Chief's Office Briefs Officials on Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The office of the chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR)
today held a meeting to brief members of the Urban Council, the
Regional Council and District Boards on the Consultation Document
on Proposals to amend the Societies Ordinance and the Public Order
Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
The office last week issued the document to solicit public
views on proposals to amend the two ordinances.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting, Michael Suen, secretary for Policy
Coordination of the office, elaborated on the major contents of
the document.
</P>
<P>
He said the decisions of the Standing Committee of the Chinese
National People's Congress (NPC) and the relevant provisions of
the Basic Law constitute the legal basis of the document.
</P>
<P>
He said the aim of the issuance of the document aims to have
the Hong Kong society achieve a balance between individual rights
and social orders.
</P>
<P>
He urged members of the councils and the boards to freely
express their views on the suggestions so as to improve the
document and ensure smooth revision of the two ordinances.
</P>
<P>
On February 23, the NPC Standing Committee resolved that under
Article 160 of the Basic Law, three sections of the Hong Kong Bill
of Rights Ordinance and major amendments to the Societies
Ordinance and the Public Order Ordinance introduced in 1992 and
1995 shall not be adopted as the laws of the HKSAR.  
</P>
</TEXT>
