<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CCB Reforms Managerial System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The China Construction Bank (CCB)
has taken a further step towards commercialization by regulating
the power limits for presidents of its branches at the provincial
level, to reform its outdated managerial system.
</P>
<P>
Wang Qishan, president of CCB, granted authorization
certificates to 45 presidents of the bank's provincial branches
today, which give a detailed explanation about their power in
business operations and personnel managment.
</P>
<P>
"Financial risks are increasing for commercial banks now, and
only an effective managerial system can prevent such risks from
happening," Wang said.
</P>
<P>
According to China's Law on Commercial Banks, the branch banks
have no status of being a legal person, and can only operate with
the authorization by its headquarters.
</P>
<P>
"The authorization system will change the management methods of
the CCB," Wang said, adding that one of the measures for the bank
is to meet the requirements as set by the Laws on Commercial Banks.
</P>
<P>
According to the rules, presidents of branch banks can only use
the power within the authorization certificates, and the branch
banks are forbidden to do any illegal businesses.
</P>
<P>
CCB will also keep a close watch on the performance of each of
its branches every year on the basis of authorization, and the
certificates will remain valid for a year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Trade Deficit Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' trade deficit in
the first two months of this year increased by 23.9 percent to
1.960 billion US dollars from 1.582 billion US dollars during the
same period of last year, the Philippine National Statistics
Office said today.
</P>
<P>
Data released by the office showed the country's imports
increased by 18.9 percent to 5.464 billion US dollars during
January-February while exports rose by 16.3 percent to 3.505
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
But the trade gap narrowed in February when the deficit stood
at 814 million US dollars, a 6.3 percent-increase compared with
766 million US dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Socio-economic Planning Secretary Cielito Habito said the
latest figures for the trade gap showed a "positive development"
as the month-on-month deficit posted a dramatic drop from 40.3
percent in January to 6.3 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
The data also showed the country's demand for electronics and
components remained high as payments increased by 42.4 percent to
471.41 million US dollars from 330.96 million US dollars last
year.
</P>
<P>
This was followed by mineral fuel, lubricants and related
materials as purchases amounted to 241.03 million US dollars from
265.75 million US dollars a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Japan was the top source for the country's imports, accounting
for 23.4 percent of the total bill for February while the United
States, with a 20.2 percent share, was the second biggest source
of imported goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
