<HEADLINE> Great Lakes Regional Summit Eases Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALLAM, April 17 (Xinhua)-- The leaders of the Great
Lakes region have agreed to ease sanctions against Burundi.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique issued in Arusha, Northern Tanzania,
yesterday at the end of a one-day summit on the Burundi crisis,
said that the sanctions have been lifted on food, agricultural
products, educational materials, medicine and constuction
materials.
</P>
<P>
The communique said the partial lifting of the embargo is
aimed at alleviating the suffering of the common people in
Burundi.
</P>
<P>
It said the move would help expedite and ensure an
uninterrupted flow of human assistance.
</P>
<P>
However, the communique said that the summit has appealed to
African nations and other countries in the world to exert full
political, economic and diplomatic presure on all factions in
Burundi for a negotiated settlement to the conflict in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
"Such presure should include an arms embargo, as well as the
denial of visas to those who are deemed to obstruct the peace
process," it said.
</P>
<P>
According to the communique, the summit stressed that
protagonists should not be armed by any party.
</P>
<P>
The regional summit called on the government of Burundi
and all other parties to the conflict to urgently take steps
towards creating an enabling environment for megotiations and
national reconciliation to take place.
</P>
<P>
The summit urged the Burundi government to disband the
"regroupment" camps and let the people resume their normal
activities without any hindrance.
</P>
<P>
The regional summit declared its readiness to suspend all
sanctions with the exception of the arms embargo once there was
progress towards a negotiated settlement.
</P>
<P>
The regional summit expressed its gratitude to President
Benjamin Mkapa and Tanzania for hosting the summit.
</P>
<P>
The summit was attended by presidents Daniel Arap Moi of
Kenya, Frederick Chiluba of Zambia, Yoweri Museveni of Uganda,
Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi and Rwandan Premier
Celestin Hwigyema.
</P>
<P>
The OAU Secretary-General, Salim A Salim, and the
international mediator on Burundi, former Tanazanian President
Julius Nyerere also attended the summit.
</P>
<P>
All heads of state left for their respective home yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Burundi leader Major Pierre Buyoya also attended the summit
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the leaders at the summit, President Mkapa said,
"Sanctions were imposed only as a tool for a specific purpose.
Sanctions were only intended to open the ears, eyes and minds of
all stakeholders in Burundi to avoid the path of mutual
annihilation."
</P>
<P>
Regional leaders imposed sanctions on landlocked Burundi on
July 31 last year, demanding Buyoya return the country to
constitutional rule and open unconditional talks with rebels.
</P>
<P>
According to a report, Buyoya has said he is ready for
unconditional talks but has not begun them. Negotiations are
opposed by hardline members of the Tutsi-dominated army and
former military ruler Jean-Baptiste Bagaza. enditem

=04171341

=04171348
NNNN
21:46 21:46 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
