<HEADLINE> China to Build Rail Telecom Net with World Bank Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Railways (MR)
will use railway loans provided by the World Bank to build a
nationwide telecom network.
</P>
<P>
The International Tendering Company of China National
Instruments Import and Export Corporation won the competitive bid
in a joint effort with China United Electric Import &AMP; Export
Corporation (CUEC) to provide program-controlled switchboards with
a capacity of 220,000 lines for MR. The contract value totaled
almost 20 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sources from MR said that the telecom network contruction is
part of the project to renovate the communication networks of
China's major rail hubs. The net is considered beneficial for
passengers and freight clients to check the railway operation,
book tickets and freight slots or follow the on-going freight
transport.
</P>
<P>
China in recent years made use of international loans provided
by international financial institutions on the country's capital
construction. The purchase, in accordance with international
bidding practices, is also one of the major orders pocketed by
local program-control switchboard producers.
</P>
<P>
All parties signed the contract on Wednesday at Beijing's
Diaoyutai State Guesthouse. The equipment is expected to be
produced and installed within the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
