<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Phase Two of NARP Launched in Kenya  (By Wang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government today
launched the phase two of the National Agricultural Research
Program (NARP II) in a bid to foster food security, poverty
reduction and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Launching the NARP II at a two-day workshop here today, Wamatu
Njoroge, Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Research,
Technical Training and Technology, said that the program is aimed
at increasing livestock and crop productivity.
</P>
<P>
During the NARP II, he noted, the program will put stress on
the development of technologies which take into account
indigenous knowledge and are oriented towards small holder
farmers.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan official pointed out that agriculture still remains
the largest sector of Kenya's economy and small holder
agriculture is the dominant mode of production.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the five-year NARP II would greatly boost
agricultural production with the improved technology which is
geared towards enabling farmers to raise the yields of their
crops.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued here today, the Director of Kenya
Agriculture Research Institute (KARI), Cyrus Nderitu, said that
KARI would stress its research emphasis on food crops such as
wheat, maize, sorghum, barley, root and tuber crops.
</P>
<P>
"KARI will focus on making improved varieties available and
develop superior, location-specific and cost-effective cultural
management practices," he added.
</P>
<P>
In his opening speech, Njoroge stressed the importance of
research, saying that research is the backbone of development in
any nation.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Kenyan government to increase investment in
research from the current level of 0.5 percent of the gross
domestic product (GDP) to two percent within next five years.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, he asked the KARI to enhance its internal
revenue generation to support its research operations in order to
avoid over-dependence on the government and donors.
</P>
<P>
Njoroge challenged KARI to ensure that in the next five years
it raises its internal revenue from the current five percent to 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
NARP II will focus on development and transfer of technology
to increase production and incomes of Kenyan small holder farmers
while HARP I which was completed in 1996 was centered on KARI's
infrastructure and developing research planning and management
systems.
</P>
<P>
The NARP is being financed by the Kenyan government and
financial institutions of the U.S., Britain, the Netherlands,
the European Union and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's agriculture sector employs about 70 percent of its
labour force and contributes some 25 percent of the country's
GDP. Agriculture also contributes indirectly to about 30 percent
of the GDP through the manufacturing and service sectors, and
about two-thirds of industrial output is from agriculture-based
industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President on Sino-Russian Ties (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On significance of bilateral cooperation in the fields of
science, education and culture, Jiang said, both Chinese and
Russian people have made great contributions to the civilization
of mankind by creating brilliant cultures with their diligence and
wisdom and, in recent years they have made great progress on the
bilateral cooperation in these fields.
</P>
<P>
Such cooperation has created good conditions for the formation
of the strategic partnership between the two countries, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, President Jiang held that the two countries will
strengthen and expand the scientific, educational and cultural
cooperation in an effort to ensure their long-term friendship,
deepen the traditional friendship of the two peoples and their
understanding of each other's national conditions, and also enrich
the substantial contents of the strategic partnership of the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Touching on the "China Threat" theory that have been spread by
certain people in the West, Jiang said that some people are not
pleased to see a strong China and have been making uproars for
imposing "containment" on China.
</P>
<P>
The true motive of those who spread such a theory is to sow
dissension among China and its neighbors in a vain attempt to
block its development, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 1.2 billion, China is the largest
developing country in the world, Jiang said. Owing to its weak
economic foundation, it requires the arduous efforts of several
generations to turn itself into a middle-developed country, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Since China is committed to advancing its economy and improving
the living standard of its people, he said, it needs a long-term,
stable international environment of peace, its good neighboring
environment in particular.
</P>
<P>
To this end, he added, China will unswervingly keep to the
independent foreign policy of peace by striving to pursue its
friendly cooperation with various countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China opposes hegemonism and power politics, and
will never seek hegemony and expansion since this is the country's
unshakable policy. And this policy will remain unchanged even when
China's economy is developed in the future.
</P>
<P>
China's stability and prosperity will pose no threat to any
country, and a developed China will contribute still more and
greater to peace and prosperity in the world, President Jiang
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
