<HEADLINE> First Municipal Elections Law Drafted in Qatar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- As the first Gulf state to
hold municipal elections, Qatar has drafted an election law to
develop "grassroot democracy" in the country.
</P>
<P>
The municipal elections are to be the first that have ever been
conducted in Qatar and unprecedented one in the political history
of the oil-rich Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
It was announced by the Qatari Emir Sheikh Hamad Ben Khalif al
Thani last year as a first step to enlist public support and
develop "grossroot democracy in the Islamic state.
</P>
<P>
"A draft law organizing municipalities and the elections is
ready and it will be submitted soon to the cabinet and advisory
council for discussion and approval," Gulf News, a daily newspaper
of the United Arab Emirates quoted today Qatari Minister of
Justice Najib bin Mohammed al-Nuaimi as saying.
</P>
<P>
Delivering a lecture on "Municipal Elections in Qatar" held
in the Qatari capital Doha Wednesday, the minister said all
Qatari citizens, including women, above 18 years will be allowed
to vote in the elections.
</P>
<P>
According to the drafted law, 21 seats of the 28-member
Central Municipal Council will be filled through the elections
while the other seven will be nominated.
</P>
<P>
"The Emir wanted all members to be elected. But after several
discussions and going by the experience of other states it was
proposed that one-fourth of the council members to be
nominated," the newspaper quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
The tenture of the elected council will be for three years
and during the period the advantages and disadvantages in its
running of the country will be examined through elections, the
minister said.
</P>
<P>
The minimum age for candidates contesting the elections has
been proposed at 25, according to the justice minister.
</P>
<P>
"A proposal is also being discussed to allow women to contest
the elections", al Nuaimi said.
</P>
<P>
Army and police personnel would not be allowed to participate
in the vote, the minister added. But he gave no reason for the
decision.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, Qatar has been reportedly taking measures
that may bring about some changes to the country's political
life.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari cabinet dissolved the Ministry of Information in
June, 1996, to give the media in the country greater autonomy,
which was regarded as an unusual move in the Arab world.
</P>
<P>
Following the dissolution, the Qatari emir appointed his
half-brother Sheikh Abdullah Ben Khalifa al Thani the prime
minister in October last year. It is the first time in the
Qatari history for the emir to relinquish his premiership and
appoint someone else to replace him.
</P>
<P>
The 47-year-old emir assumed power of the country after
ousting his father Khalifa Bin Hamad al Thani in a bloodless
palace coup in June, 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Shares Edge Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
moved slightly higher today with the tone of the market remaining
cautious despite a strong gain on Wall Street overnight.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark All Ordinaries Index closed 6.8 points up at
2413.2, with the All Industrials Index jumping 12.3 points to
3802.1 and the All Resources 2.3 points to 1341.3.
</P>
<P>
"It is showing a little bit of resilience but overall I would
think it's fully valued and will stay volatile as people speculate
on how much the U.S. Federal Reserve raises the interest rate by,"
said Anton Tagliaferro from BHP Investments.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. market was becoming increasingly sensitive to figures
and data, with regard to interest rate rises and inflationary
pressures.
</P>
<P>
In the local banking sector, National Australia Bank moved 17
cents higher, Commonwealth Bank shed 3 cents, Westpac was a cent
lower and ANZ rose a cent.
</P>
<P>
The gold index was 0.4 points lower at 1556.2, with gold
bullion closing at 342 U.S. dollars an ounce from 341.5
previously.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 297.74 million shares valued at
773.14 million Australian dollars (603.04 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
