<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian President Backs Corridor Linking Europe, Central </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu has supported the idea of turning Romania into a
corridor linking East and West Europe with Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
The president, said an official ROMPRES news agency report
today, discussed the proposal raised by Transport Minister Traian
Basescu in a meeting with his advisors late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Romania will propose to Central and West European countries to
open up an economic corridor for transport between former Soviet
republics and Europe, Constantinescu was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The corridor, to start from Kazakhstan, go through Azerbaijan,
Georgia and the Black Sea, and end up at the Romanian port of
Constanta, is expected to boost economic exchanges between Europe
and Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
With its opening, the ROMPRES report said, crude oil and cotton
from Central Asia could be shipped directly to West Europe.
</P>
<P>
As part of Romania's initiative, Basescu told reporters on
April 11, after a meeting in Georgia with his counterparts from
countries in the region, that there will be regular shipping
liners between Constanta and the Georgian port of Poti. 
</P>
</TEXT>
