<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grottos Near Dunhuang to Be Open in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Yulin Grottos, neighboring the
world-famous Dunhuang Grottos in northwest China's Gansu Province,
will be open to the public in July.
</P>
<P>
The grottos are located in the Yulin valley, 76 kilometers to
the south of Anxi County, which is about 100 km to the northeast
of Dunhuang.
</P>
<P>
A total of 43 caves on cliffs along the valley contain 259
colored statues and some 4,200 square meters of wall paintings,
which represent Buddhism, farming, wine-making, iron forging, and
images of birds and plants, according to researchers of Yulin
Grottos.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the grottos, now under the state protection, dated
back to the Sui Dynasties (581-618), the Tang (618-907), the Song
(960-1279), the Western Xia (1038-1227), and the Yuan (1271-1368).
</P>
<P>
The shape of the caves and contents and artistic styles of the
wall paintings in Yulin showed that Yulin Grottos have a very
close link with the art of Dunhuang Grottos.
</P>
<P>
Research of Yulin Grottos will be an important part of Dunhuang
research, which is popular in domestic and overseas academic
circles at present.
</P>
<P>
The Dunhuang Grottos, built from the 6th to the 14th century,
include some 2,000 colored statues and more than 40,000 sq.m. of
wall paintings. The Dunhuang Grottos are on the World Heritage
List.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
