<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negotiation, or Separatism in Name of Negotiation? (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A commentator's article released
by Xinhua today repudiated the Dalai Lama's remarks over recent
years which encourage separatism under the guise of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Following is the full text of the article:
</P>
<P>
The exiled Dalai Lama has claimed repeatedly in recent years
that he wants to negotiate with the Chinese central government,
which is nothing new.
</P>
<P>
The Dalai Lama has proposed conducting "negotiations" with the
central government off and on for the past decade along with the
changes of the international climate. Especially in recent years,
he has widely spread his claims and made efforts to blame the
central government for not having conducted negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, there is a need to clarify facts and expose the
Dalai Lama's political trickery, which encourages divisiveness
under the guise of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
In September of 1987 and June of 1988, the Dalai Lama proposed
a "Five-Point Plan" at a meeting of the Human Rights Sub-committee
of the US House of Representatives, and "New Proposals" at a press
conference at the European Parliament building in Strasbourg,
France.
</P>
<P>
On both occasions, he claimed to hold negotiations with the
central government based on the "Five-Point Plan" and the "New
Proposals."
</P>
<P>
The central government pointed out that the "Five-Point Plan"
and the "New Proposals" in fact advocated "Independence of Tibet"
and the notion that "Tibet was an independent country in history."
</P>
<P>
The essence of the Dalai Lama's position was the denial of the
fact that Tibet is a part of Chinese territory and that the
Chinese government has full sovereignty over Tibet.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the central government announced the
following principles:
</P>
<P>
First, it welcomes the Dalai Lama and his representatives to
negotiate with the central government at any time, but that the
government will not receive the delegation sent in the name of the
"Kasha Government", because the central government has never
recognized that "Government", which is in exile;
</P>
<P>
Second, because the Dalai Lama's "Five-Point Plan" and the "New
Proposals" do not renounce "Independence of Tibet," they can not
be regarded as a basis for negotiations;
</P>
<P>
Third, the central government wants to have a direct dialogue
with the Dalai Lama, and the talks could be held either in Beijing
or in Hong Kong, or at any Chinese embassy or consulate. If the
Dalai Lama finds any of these places inconvenient, he can choose
another venue, as long as foreigners are excluded from the
meetings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negotiation, or Separatism in Name of Negotiation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When the Central Government announced that the time and place
of negotiations would be chosen by the Dalai Lama, he and his
followers soon put a notice in a newspaper saying that they would
negotiate with the Central Government in Geneva in January of 1989.
</P>
<P>
But the Central Government did not receive any formal
notification until after the news was printed, and the connection
between the Central Government and the Dalai Lama was not cut then
and had been maintained ever since it was formed in 1978.
</P>
<P>
If the Dalai Lama was sincere about holding the talks, why
didn't he convey this information and make arrangements through
proper channels? His actions could not help causing people to
doubt him and to wonder whether he really wanted to participate in
the talks or just to use the call for negotiations as a publicity
stunt.
</P>
<P>
When the Tenth Panchen Lama passed away in early 1989, the
Buddhist Association of China invited the Dalai Lama to return to
China to attend funeral services, and its President Zhao Puchu
handed over in person a letter of invitation to the representative
of the Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
The invitation dealt solely with religious affairs. But the
Dalai Lama, if he had truly been sincere about holding talks,
could have taken the opportunity to contact Central Government
representatives. But he refused the invitation.
</P>
<P>
In March of 1988 and again in March of 1989, riots broke out in
Lhasa, instigated by a small group of separatists. Evidences show
that the Dalai Lama's "government in exile" not only provided
financial support to the separatists, but also sent people to
plan, organize, and participate in the riots that aimed at
splitting the motherland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0125 </DOCNO>
