<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negotiation, or Separatism in Name of Negotiation? (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the wake of a wave of anti-Chin sentiment abroad from the
late 1980s to the early 1990s, the Dalai Lama went hither and
thither to ask Western countries to apply pressure on the Chinese
government.
</P>
<P>
He also changed his attitude to the negotiation, saying that he
was not eager to negotiate with the central government because it
would "collapse" soon.
</P>
<P>
However, the development of China's domestic situation did not
follow his wishes and his prediction came to naught. Seeing
China's international status improving with its economic growth
and social stability, the Dalai Lama asked for renewed contacts
with the central government.
</P>
<P>
Chinese departments concerned received two visits paid by his
private representative in 1992 and in 1993, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Before the negotiations, the representative promised not to
make the negotiation contents public. Later, however, the
representative not only released the negotiation contents, but
also wantonly distorted the contents in an attempt to mislead the
public.
</P>
<P>
In the second half of 1993, the Dalai Lama unilaterally
announced his decision to discontinue all contacts with the
central government, closing the door to contacts and negotiations
by his own hands.
</P>
<P>
On the question of negotiations requested by Dalai, the Chinese
government has reiterated repeatedly that it may negotiate with
him and has welcomed him to end his exile and return to the
motherland at an early date to do things beneficial to the Tibetan
people, provided that he completely abandons his notion of
"Tibetan Independence" and recognizes that Tibet is an inseparable
part of China, and ceases to engage in his activities to split the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
The central government's principled stand and basic attitude
have always been consistent and explicit, and the Dalai Lama is
clear about them.
</P>
<P>
He should be held entirely responsible for the suspension of
the negotiations and fruitlessness in the two-sided contacts over
the past ten-plus years, because he has not abandoned his stand to
seek "Tibetan Independence" and or stopped his political
activities to split the motherland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0128 </DOCNO>
