<HEADLINE> Filipino-Chinese Economic Contribution Praised </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Finance Secretary
Roberto de Ocampo today lauded the economic contribution of the
Filipino-Chinese community to the country's economic progress.
</P>
<P>
The Filipino Chinese comprise only about two percent of the
total Philippine population, but they have an economic clout that
far exceeds their numerical might, de Ocampo said at a meeting
with the Filipino-Chinese business community.
</P>
<P>
"I would say that the Filipino-Chinese community has become an
indispensable and integral part of the Philippine economy," he
said. "It is inconceivable how the Philippine economy would fare
without the Filipino-Chinese community."
</P>
<P>
Citing an Ateneo de Manila University study, he revealed that
as of 1990, 354 or 35.4 percent of the top 1,000 corporations in
the country were owned by Filipino-Chinese.
</P>
<P>
De Ocampo said the economic ascendancy of the Filipino-Chinese
is best exemplified by the rise of the so-called taipans, the most
successful of the lot, who have made huge interests in a wide
variety of businesses.
</P>
<P>
The government has recognized these pioneering entrepreneurs as
vital cogs of the economy and assigned them new projects that
would help the country become a newly industrialized economy by
the year 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
The finance secretary also emphasized that the exemplary role
of the Filipino-Chinese community is needed in the globalization
of economies in order to successfully compete.  
</P>
</TEXT>
