<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negotiation, Or Separatism in Name of Negotiation? (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In recent years, Dalai has continued to move from one place to
another, reviving his claim that he wants to hold negotiations
with the central government, and that he is only asking for
autonomy for Tibet and does not stick to seeking Tibet
independence.
</P>
<P>
However, he has continued to distort the history of Tibet on
various public occasions and has attempted to create public opinions
for "Tibetan independence" by taking every opportunity to spread
the idea that "Tibet has always been an independent country since
ancient times."
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, Tibet has been an integral part of Chinese
territory since ancient times and became one of China's
administrative regions in the mid-13th century.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 700 years, the central government has effectively
exercised sovereignty over Tibet. The Dalai Lama's title and his
religious and political status in Tibet were granted by the
central government. The 14th Dalai Lama, Danzin Gyaco, was
enthroned in the 1940s with the approval by the then central
government.
</P>
<P>
While claiming to ask for negotiations with the central
government, Dalai has continued to engage in activities abroad to
split the motherland. The Dalai Lama and his followers have never
stopped their propaganda and instigation to split the motherland
in the Tibetan Autonomous Region, and have been held responsible
for stirring up acts of violence and terrorism, such as riots and
explosions in Lhasa and other places, and have plotted the
so-called "peace marches" and "referendums" abroad.
</P>
<P>
In their attempt to internationalize the so-called "Tibet
issue," they have asked for international forces to become
involved in the "Tibetan issue." Moreover, the Dalai Lama went to
Taiwan in late March in an open attempt at collusion with "Taiwan
independence" forces within the island of Taiwan, and plotted to
set up an office there for his "government-in-exile." His visit
was warmly received by politicians of the Taiwan authorities.
</P>
<P>
Public opinion overseas has pointed out that, on the surface,
the Dalai Lama alleged that his visit to Taiwan was purely for
religious purposes, but his intention of seeking "Tibetan
independence" and attempt to break away from the Chinese
government were quite clear. He was involved in a number of covert
activities in this respect, in sharp contrast to his words.
</P>
<P>
Public opinion overseas has also revealed that one of Dalai's
former "government officials" asked Taiwan authorities to
officially abolish the "Commission on Mongolian and Tibetan
Affairs," and "jointly pursue the ideal of independence" with
him.
</P>
</TEXT>
