<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water-saving Irrigation Essential to Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior official urged
agro-colleges and technicians to work out various forms of
water-saving irrigation techniques and machines for farmers in the
northern part of China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese vice-premier Li Lanqing raised the request in a letter
to a meeting on popularizing water-saving irrigation techniques
held this week by the Ministry of Agriculture in Chifeng, in north
China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Agriculture planned to apply water-saving
irrigation technology in 50 million mu (about 3.3 million
hectares) of land in north China during the Ninth Five-Year Plan
(1996-2000). Mechanized dry farming technology will also be used
in 160 million mu (about 10.7 million hectares) of land, an
increase of 100 percent compared with the current situation.
</P>
<P>
Li said that to popularize water-saving irrigation and dry
farming technology in dry north China will help promote sustained
development of China's agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The average water resource per person in 16 northern provinces
was only about 300 cubic meters, meaning half of the country's
provinces, autonomous regions, and municipalities are short of
water resources.
</P>
<P>
Almost two thirds of China's arable land are located in areas
with annual rainfall of less than 600 millimeters. Grain yields of
these areas are low and unstable due to the shortage of water.
</P>
<P>
"It is an important measure to make full use of limited water
resource to develop China's agriculture," said Li, who is also
member of the Political Bureau of the Central Committee of the
Communist Party of China (CPC). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
