<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Upper House Passes Okinawa Land Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan's House of Councillors, or
the upper house of parliament, today adopted a government-proposed
bill allowing continued compulsory use of land by the U.S.
military in Okinawa Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
The revised bill on land lease, already approved by the more
powerful House of Representatives, or the lower house of
parliament, became a law after it cleared the upper house.
</P>
<P>
It is designed to allow the central government to continue to
occupy land within U.S. bases in the island prefecture even after
lease contracts expire on May 14.
</P>
<P>
The bill was passed amid strong protest by some 200
demonstrators, including about 30 lawyers from Okinawa, Tokyo and
Osaka, who staged a sit-in outside the upper house building in
downtwon Tokyo, urging Juro Sito, president of the upper house, to
give careful consideration to the revised bill.
</P>
<P>
Members of the upper house's two large opposition groups,
Heiseikai and the Democratic Party of Japan (DJP), voted for the
bill, supporting the ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and New
Party Sakigake, one of the LDP's two noncabinet allies.
</P>
<P>
Heiseikai is mainly composed of members of the largest
opposition party, the New Frontier Party (NFP).
</P>
<P>
However, members of the Social Democratic Party, the other
noncabinet ally of the LDP, and the Japanese Communist Party voted
against the bill while some 3,000 owners of the land now occupied
by 12 U.S. bases were opposed to renewing the lease.
</P>
<P>
Observers say the bill will further a gap between the central
government and Okinawa's local government.
</P>
<P>
Okinawa is home to 75 percent of all U.S. military facilities
in Japan, as more than 47,000 U.S. troops in Japan are stationed
there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
