<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Use Fish to Fight Malaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A kind of fish, which eats
mosquito larvae, has been used to control malaria in experiments
in India, V. P. Sharma, director of India's Malaria Research
Center (MRC), said.
</P>
<P>
The MRC, which functions under the Indian Council of Medical
Research, initially started a project on integrated control of
malaria in Gujarat in 1983.
</P>
<P>
Its success led to extension of the project, subsequently, to
more than 12 locations across the country, according to the Press
Trust of India.
</P>
<P>
Sharma said scientists from the center have been able to reduce
malaria incidence dramatically in areas where the project was
carried out.
</P>
<P>
Cases of malaria have dropped by 80 percent in 152 villages
(population 55,000) in Hassan District of Karnataka State within
one year of introducing the larvae-eating fish, Sharma said.
</P>
</TEXT>
