<HEADLINE> AL Chief Invokes Memory of Qana Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary General
Esmat Abdul-Meguid today urged Arab countries to unite behind
Lebanon's struggle against the Israeli occupation on the eve of
the first anniversary of an Israeli air raid in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"April 18 must be observed as an Arab Day of Solidarity with
the Lebanese people in its struggle to restore its lands," said
Meguid in a speech to mark the 1996 Qana carnage.
</P>
<P>
About 100 men, women and children were killed on April 18,
1996 when Israeli gunners shelled a U.N. camp in Qana, south
Lebanon where 400 villagers had sought shelter.
</P>
<P>
The incident is the most serious one between the two countries
since the Israeli invasion of Lebanon in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Meguid urged the U.N. Security Council to force Israel to
implement its resolutions, especially those related to the
Arab-Israeli conflict and to the Palestinian cause, namely
resolutions 242, 338 and 425.
</P>
<P>
He also urged the United States, the main Mideast peace
sponsor, the European Union, Russia, China and Japan to face up
to the Israeli measures which "aim at clamping a fait accompli by
military force in the occupied Arab lands" something which
threatens Arab security and stability.
</P>
<P>
Meguid today sent cables to Lebanese President Elias Hrawi and
Prime Minister Rafik Hariri and Speaker of the Parliament Nabih
Berri, expressing the AL's full support for Lebanon in its
legitimate rights to restore all of its lands.
</P>
<P>
Israel, seeking an end to cross-border attacks on northern
Israel by the fundamentalist guerrilla of Hezbollah, wants a
peace agreement with Lebanon and Syria, which will give it
accords with all its immediate neighbors.
</P>
<P>
But Lebanon and Syria have put the return of all Lebanese
territory and the Golan Heights Israel has occupied as the
prerequisite of peace deal with the Jewish state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
