<HEADLINE> China to Sponsor Water Resources Art Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China's Ministry of Water
Resources, with its 1.6 million workers, will soon start its art
festival, believing that cultural development also helps harness
rivers and lakes.
</P>
<P>
The festival, the second in three years, will include contests
of singing, dancing, calligraphy, drawing, drama, and literature.
</P>
<P>
Most of the contests will be held on the major construction
sites on the Yangtze River, Yellow River, and Liaohe and Huaihe
rivers.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges project on the Yangtze, and the Wanjiazhai and
Xiaolangdi water conservation projects on the Yellow River will be
the key performing stages during the festival, which lasts from
late April to November.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by Li Changfan, an official of the ministry
in a press conference today.
</P>
<P>
He said that the art festival will be held at a time when
several major historical events are to take place in the country,
which include the resumption of China's sovereignty over Hong Kong
and the convocation of the 15th National Congress of the Chinese
Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
The events will make the harnessing of the rivers and lakes the
paramount task to the ministry, he said, and the ministry is
trying hard to ensure that "no big problems will crop up."
</P>
<P>
The official said that China expects more rainfall this year in
southern China, which straddles the Yangtze and the Huaihe rivers,
and that the ministry starts implementing flood control measures
earlier than last year.
</P>
<P>
"Currently, all major leaders of our ministry are in the
localities to inspect the implementation of such measures," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
