<HEADLINE> Major Chinese Cities to Ban Leaded Gasoline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Major Chinese cities will
introduce the use of unleaded auto gasoline by the year 2000 in an
effort to reduce air pollution caused by auto emission, according
to a report in today's "China Youth Daily".
</P>
<P>
The cities of Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Wuhan, and Shenzhen
will take the lead in fulfilling this goal in the next year, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Rapid growth of the number of motor vehicles and wide use of
leaded gas have led to severe air pollution in Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
About 65 percent of the lead content in the air over Beijing is
discharged by some 1.1 million autos in the city, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou-based "Yangcheng Evening News" recently said that
900,000 motor vehicles in this metropolis of south China used one
million tons of leaded gasoline annually.
</P>
<P>
Lead containing in auto emission exhaust is blamed as one of
the major "criminals" doing injury to urban residents' health.
</P>
<P>
Inhalation of Lead-rich emission can cause high level of lead
content in blood, which is very harmful to the human body,
particularly to pregnant women and newly-borns, said Yu Xiaoxuan,
deputy director of the Beijing Bureau of Environmental Protection.
</P>
<P>
The bureau has announced that about 300 gas stations in
Beijing's eight urban districts will have to sell lead-free
gasoline up to July 1. Unleaded gas will be used all across the
city by January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The environmental protection authority in Guangzhou also
decided to take the same measure in October, said the report of
Yangcheng Evening News. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
