<HEADLINE> Hundreds of Rebels in S. Leone Want to Give </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Freetown, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of Sierra Leone
rebels, particularly in the north and south, are wanting to
surrender to the government, a surrendered Revolutionary United
Front (RUF) combatant, Mohamed Kargbo, said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking to foreign correspondents who were flown to
Magbunaka in the north of the country by military helicopter to
interview the surrendered rebels.
</P>
<P>
''We want to do everything that can bring peace to our
country,'' says 13-year-old Alhaji Kamara whose skin was covered
with scabies.
</P>
<P>
Another surrendered combatant, Some Fornah, says ''we decided
to take the risk to give ourselves up as we were slowly dying
from hunger. There is hardly any food in the (rebels) bases and
we were just starving."
</P>
<P>
International relief non-governmental organisations have
rushed in food supplies to Magburaka, a dusty junction town by
road and air, to prevent what one official called ''a pending
human disaster''.
</P>
<P>
Reports said some rebels are surrendring to tribal chiefs.
</P>
<P>
According to the Sierra Leone Red Cross, ''the surrender is
almost on a daily basis ''.
</P>
<P>
Twentyseven rebels surrendered on Tuesday in the villages of
Mayopoh, Mayombo and Macrugbe before they were taken to the Adams
hotel, a relief offcial, Sam Bockarie, said.
</P>
<P>
The rebels are mainly coming from Kangari Hills, which
overlooks a strategic road linking the capital with the
diamond-rich fields of Kono in the east.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said those surrendering include not only
compatants but senior ranking officials.
