<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Strengthen Protection of Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese State Council called
today for better protection of the country's cultural relics,
which are the invaluable heritage of a 5,000-year-old civilization.
</P>
<P>
It said that the number of crimes involving relics is growing,
that many museum pieces have been stolen, and that a number of
tombs have been illegally dug up, while smuggling of relics is
still running rampant.
</P>
<P>
"We must do a better job of balancing relics protection and
economic construction," it says, and that the country's policemen
need to crack down on relics crimes.
</P>
<P>
There should be better cooperation between the police, customs,
business, trade departments, and relics bureaus, it points out,
and the governments at all levels should play a major role in
protecting relics, with everybody in the community participating.
</P>
<P>
More laws should be drafted and governments at various levels
must observe the laws. The relation between excavations and
economic construction should be handled properly, and the
protection of historical sites should not add a burden to people
living nearby.
</P>
<P>
Construction projects can not proceed until they get approval
from relics departments, it says.
</P>
<P>
The country will allocate funds for protecting important relics
and historical sites which are at the verge of being damaged.
</P>
<P>
Profitable ventures must be avoided if they stand to damage
relics, and historical sites should be used as patriotic places,
it says.
</P>
<P>
The government should adopt measures to control the relics
market, including auctions, it says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Peruvian Congress Leaders Hails Bilateral Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of the Standing
Committee of China's National People's Congress (NPC) Qiao Shi
said here today that he believes the current visit of the
president of the Peruvian Congress Victor Joyway Rojas will make
great contributions to developing the friendship between the
congresses of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting between the two congresses leaders, Qiao said
he is pleased with the smooth parliamentary cooperation between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Qiao said despite of the long distance between China and Peru,
the two countries enjoy deep friendship. They should step up
exchanges and strengthen the friendly relations, he added.
</P>
<P>
Joyway showed his admiration of China's growth, and said he
would bring back China's experience in developing the economy and
alleviating poverty.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the reform and opening up program, Qiao
pointed out, China has achieved great development under the
guidance of the theory of "building socialism with Chinese
characteristics," which was initiated by Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
He said China has vast land and 1.2 billion people, and
therefore China's real modernization calls for the efforts of
several generations.
</P>
<P>
Joyway praised China's independent foreign policy of peace, and
congratulated on the approaching return of Hong Kong and Macao to
the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Peru sticks to the "one China" position, he stressed, and holds
that Taiwan is an unseparable part of the Chinese territory. He
said he hopes China will achieve national reunification at an
early date.
</P>
<P>
Joyway is here as guest of the NPC Standing Committee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
