<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Euro-Med Cooperation Tides Over Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VALLETTA, MALTA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The
European-Mediterranean cooperation partners have tided over a
political crisis threatening their ambitious cooperation scheme
during the just-concluded Malta conference.
</P>
<P>
After two-day harsh discussions, ministers from all the 27
Euro-Med cooperation members reached agreement to address the
thorny Middle East peace process in measured terms, leaving out
the criticism on hard-line policy contained in a draft final
document of the conference.
</P>
<P>
Arab countries had insisted that the final document should
include the faltering Middle East developments and Israel
objected.
</P>
<P>
The hot debate on the issue dominated the conference, which
the European Union (EU) had wanted to focus on the economic
dimension in Euro-Med cooperation, forcing a five-hour delay upon
the closing ceremony -- and without a final document.
</P>
<P>
Still, under the circumstance of an unfavorable Middle East
peace stalemate, the gathering of all the members together in
itself is great, many delegation heads said.
</P>
<P>
Another major achievement the EU boasts was the successful
bringing together of Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli
Foreign Minister David Levy to a bilateral meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Arafat-Levy meeting is the first direct political dialog
between the Palestinian National Authority and Israel since the
peace process came to the lowest ebb in its seven-year history a
month ago. Arab countries have suspended their normalization
process of relations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
By brokering the meeting, observers here noted, the EU
added a point on its score board of advancing its "Focus-shift
Southwards" strategy aimed at counterbalancing United States'
influence in the region.
</P>
<P>
Western analysts said a good opportunity has arrived for
Europe to seek a more active involvement in the Middle East
-- at a time when the United States gives bias to Israel
in mediation at the cost of losing Arab trust in it.
</P>
<P>
"We are happy that Europe can play a complimentary role
to that of the United States (in Mideast mediation)," said a
grinning Hans Van Mierlo, foreign minister of EU rotary
president of the Netherlands, at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the positive conclusion of the Malta
conference in itself is a contribution to the Middle East
process.
</P>
<P>
Many delegations, particularly from EU members, stressed common
interests in Euro-Med cooperation in attempt to boost the low
morale among some southern Mediterranean partners, who are
overwhelmed by fears of being robbed of benefits in cooperation.
Mierlo said the partners have to come together "for the sake
of the future of the two regions."
</P>
<P>
The delegates confirmed the progress achieved since their
first Barcelona conference in November 1995. Many called for
valuing the North-South type EU-Med cooperation and the
South-South type cooperation among Mediterranean countries themselves,
which are still fragile to various difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Anyway, Maltese Prime Minister Alfred Sant said in his
closing speech that the Malta conference has demonstrated that
the Euro-Med Partnership is "an irreversible process" of
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During the Malta conference, the EU and Jordan initialed a
partnership-linked Association Agreement. This brings to eight the
number of countries which reached such accords with EU in
the Euro-Med cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The concept of Euro-Med partnership was initiated at the
Barcelona conference with an aim of establishing a free-trade
zone involving the two regions by the year 2010, a goal also
confirmed at the Malta conference.
</P>
<P>
It is generally believed that despite the political
achievement in Malta conference, the Euro-Med cooperation will be
shadowed by the Mideast Peace as long as it is there. The
existing huge political, economic and social disparities between
the EU countries and their Mediterranean neighbors are even more
a daily headache for them. Therefore, observers here said, the
road ahead for the EU-Med cooperation is rather long and
tough.
</P>
<P>
EU's 12 Mediterranean partners are Algeria, Cyprus, Egypt,
Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Malta, Morocco, Syria, Tunisia, Turkey
and Palestine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
