<HEADLINE> Australia Wins Record Uranium Contract With Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Australia's mining major WMC
Ltd. today clinched a record uranium contract in a 10-year deal to
supply Tokyo Electric Power Co. with 907 tons per year from 1999.
</P>
<P>
The contract was won on the strength of uranium production at
its massive Olympic Dam copper and uranium mine, which currently
produces 1,500 tons of uranium a year, but the output will rise to
more than 4,600 tons a year by 1999 when the expansion at the mine
is completed.
</P>
<P>
WMC Managing Director Hugh Morgan said in a statement that this
is the largest single contract ever for the Olympic Dam mine.
</P>
<P>
However, environmentalists in Australia today hit out at the
federal government for approving the record uranium supply
contract with Tokyo after the cover-up of Japan's worst nuclear
accident last month.
</P>
<P>
West Australian Green Senator Dee Margetts said they were
surprised that radioactive leaks at an experimental converter
reactor in Japan went unreported and the country's worst nuclear
accident last month was covered up.  
</P>
