<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Human Rights Group Blasts Israel's Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 17 (April) -- The Arab Organization of Human
Rights (AOHR) has renewed its warning that Israel's
"expansionist" policy and violation of human rights would
strangle the Mideast peace process and escalate instability.
</P>
<P>
The organization billed the construction of the Har Homa
Jewish neighborhood in East Jerusalem as a vital step that Israel
has taken to Judaize the holy city and create a fait accompli by
changing its geographical and demographical features.
</P>
<P>
"The end of the scheme is to turn the eastern and western
sectors of Jerusalem into a permanent capital of the Jewish
state," it noted in a report released here today.
</P>
<P>
The report described the Israeli decision to build the 6,500
Jewish homes on the edge of East Jerusalem as an "extremely
dangerous move" that preempts the Palestinian-Israeli final talks
to resolve such sensitive problems as Jerusalem and Palestinian
statehood.
</P>
<P>
"It will extinguish the Palestinian confidence in Israel's
true will for peace negotiations and cast doubt over the need to
continue talks on a final peace between the two sides," it warned.
</P>
<P>
The report stressed the Israeli practice might explode the
already-tense Mideast situation, aggravating violence and
renewing the 1980s' uprisings on the Palestinian occupied lands.
</P>
<P>
The AOHR denounced the Israeli settlement buildings on the
Palestinian land and the Judaization practices of Jerusalem,
saying that they not only violate the international law and U.N.
resolutions but also contradict Palestinian-Israeli agreements.
</P>
<P>
The Mideast peace has plunged into its deepest crisis since
Israel started last month the Jewish housing construction, thus
stalling the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks and sparking almost
daily clashes on the occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
Palestine want East Jerusalem, which Israel has captured and
later annexed, as its future capital. But Israel has insist that
the holy city be its "permanent and undivided capital." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
