<HEADLINE> Tibetan NPC Vice-Chairman Meets with Nepalese Guests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lhasa, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Puqung, vice-chairman of the
Standing Committee of the Tibet Autonomous Regional People's
Congress, met here Wednesday with a delegation from the Nepalese
Parliament to discuss their relationship, which spans 12 centuries.
</P>
<P>
Puqung described China and Nepal as the close neighbors that
have a traditional friendship. Frequent exchanges of high-level
visits and growing contacts in many fields have increased mutual
understanding and friendly cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Anand, leader of the Nepali group, said the Nepali-Chinese
relationship can be traced back to the Seventh century and that it
is deeply rooted in Nepalese culture, with China as the most
important neighboring country.
</P>
<P>
The Nepalese government considers Tibet an inseparable part of
China and forbids any anti-Chinese activities on its soil, he
said, adding that to develop economic cooperative ties with Tibet
is in Nepal's interest, he added.
</P>
<P>
During its stay in Tibet, the delegation visited the Potala
Palace and other famous scenic spots. They arrived here Tuesday as
guests of the Foreign Affairs Committee of the Chinese National
People's Congress Standing Committee. 
</P>
