<HEADLINE> Most HK People Prefer to Stay Home, Survey Shows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 17 (Xinhua) -- An overwhelming 81 percent of
Hong Kong respondents had no plans to emigrate, indicating an
overall optimism over the territory's future, a survey of 13
Asia-Pacific economies by MasterCard International found.
</P>
<P>
Only 15 percent of Hong Kong respondents said they wished to
emigrate, below the regional average of 16 percent, while a
remaining 4 percent were undecided, according to the survey.
</P>
<P>
"The Hong Kong emigration figures, particularly when compared
to the likes of Singapore, the Republic of Korea (ROK) and Japan, are
very surprising indeed," said a spokesman for the credit-card
company.
</P>
<P>
The survey showed that 17 percent of Japanese, 19 percent of
Singaporeans, 20 percent of South Koreans, 28 percent of Indians
and 33 percent of Filipinos were keen to emigrate.  
</P>
</TEXT>
