<HEADLINE> Indonesia's MMR to Drop, Says Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The maternal mortality rate (MMR)
in Indonesia is expected to drop to 2.25 per 1,000 by the end of
the sixth five-year development plan in 1999, a government
official said.
</P>
<P>
The government has treated the mother and child care as a
priority in the past 25 years, the local press today quoted
Secretary General of the Health Ministry Hidayat Hardjoprawito as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's MMR is now at 3.7 per 1,000 and its Infant
mortality rate (IMR) is at 58 per 1,000.
</P>
<P>
The official said the Health Ministry had launched a program to
increase the number of nurses in villages in an effort to reduce
the mortality rates.
</P>
<P>
About 50,000 villages of the total of 67,000 villages in the
country are currently provided with nurses.
</P>
<P>
"We have been on the right track on the mother and child care,"
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
