<HEADLINE> France Backs Easing EU Sanctions on Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- France has pledged to lobby its
partners in the European Union (EU) to relax their sanctions on
Nigeria, the Daily Champion reported today.
</P>
<P>
French Ambassador to Nigeria, Philipe Peltier, reportedly made
the promise in a visit to Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi in
Abuja on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He, however, said his country will not go to the extent of
provoking the EU countries, but will explain the current
situation in Nigeria so as to make them have a realistic
position.
</P>
<P>
EU countries imposed sanctions on Nigeria after it hanged
author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight other Ogoni activists on murder
charges in November 1995.
</P>
<P>
The French ambassador also explained that the Bakassi
territory crisis between English-speaking Nigeria and neighboring
French-speaking Cameroun is their "own problem", saying France
would only play an observing role.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has accused France of involvement in the conflict
between it and Cameroun over the oil-rich peninsula, which both
countries claim as its own territory.
</P>
<P>
The French ambassador also commended Nigeria on the successful
conduct of the March 15 local government election and its leading
role in restoring peace in Liberia, the newspaper said. 
</P>
