<HEADLINE> Mozambican Cotton Companies Reject "Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A cotton crisis is looming over
Mozambique as the local cotton processing companies refused to
purchase cotton at the minimum prices set by the government,
local paper "Noticias" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Henriques, an official of Lomaco Cotton Company, said
the government policy on cotton will bring about serious
consequences to cotton production as a whole.
</P>
<P>
It will not only suffocate cotton processing enterprises, but
will also discourage cotton farmers, many of whom might stop
growing cotton, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Henriques warned that if the lowest price of cotton set by the
government, 3,900 Meticais (about 0.35 U.S. Dollar) per kilogram
of raw cotton, is maintained this year, some cotton processing
plants will be forced to close down.
</P>
<P>
He said as the prices set by the government are much higher
than in the international market, Lomaco and other cotton
companies have decided to refused to buy cotton at the minimum
prices.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the Mozambique Cotton Association and
cotton companies have made their proposals on cotton prices,
which have not been accepted by the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
