<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka to Abolish Executive Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan Minister of Justice
and Constitutional Affairs G. l. Peiris has said the country's
present executive presidency will be abolished under a new
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters here today on the principal features of the
government's new draft constitution for Sri Lanka, Peiris said
some of the more salient features are the strengthening of
democratic institutions and abolition of the executive presidency
in order to restore the authority of parliament.
</P>
<P>
Under the draft constitution, the role of the president would
be a ceremonial one and he or she who would be elected through a
two-third majority in parliament, would have to act on the advice
of the prime minister, as was the case in the republican
constitution of 1972, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The minister added that President Chandrika Kumaratunga wanted
the new draft constitution presented in parliament prior to the
budget this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
