<HEADLINE> Coca-Cola Jordan Falls Into Foreign Hands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Local owners of Giant Coca-Cola
Jordan company has finalized a deal relinquishing all their shares
to two foreign firms, making it one of the first wholly
foreign-owned enterprises in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola Near East company has announced that the owner of
National Company for Bottling Carbonated Drinks and Food Stuffs
(Coca-Cola Jordan), a group of prominent Jordanian businessmen,
sold the bottling establishment to Faroise de Consentre, a French
division of Coca-Cola International, and the United Soft Drinks
Production, an American company, Jordan's news agency Petra
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The takeover by the two foreign companies representing a
multinational corporation is one of the first in Jordan, under a
new foreign investment incentive law introduced last year. Before
the new law was adopted, foreign companies were allowed to hold no
more than 49 percent of the equity in any company based in the
Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Following the acquisition, a multi-million-dollar investment
plan to expand production in Jordan was announced, thus more job
opportunities will be created for the Jordanians.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola officials said this move will also beneficial to
Jordanians whose demand for Coca-Cola's brands soft drinks is on
the rise.
</P>
<P>
"This is not only a sign of our confidence in Jordan. but also
a sign of coca-cola's committment to the Jordanian people,"
Phipippe Georgiou, Coca-Cola Near East Region Manager, said.
</P>
<P>
Azem Omar Yousef, a former manager at the bottling plant in
the United Arab Emirates, will assume his post as general manager
of the company.
</P>
<P>
Coca-Cola entered the Jordanian market in 1993, and has been
striving to compete with Pepsi-Cola, another American-made soft
drink, which enjoyed a nearly 30-year monopoly in the Kingdom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
