<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tension Grows with 44 Dead in Nigerian Ethnic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Tension heightened again in
Nigeria's southern oil city of Warri on Wednesday following
reports of the killing of 44 Ijaw people in the continuing
clashes between ethnic communities.
</P>
<P>
The Ijaw group alleged that 42 persons were killed when a town
in Delta State was torched by unknown people last Saturday, while
two others were murdered in the troubled area.
</P>
<P>
According to the group, about 80 attackers alighted from a
fast boat belonging to an oil company and another high-powered
boat on the Ikpokpo Jetty, armed with guns, cutlasses, bottles
and gallons of petrol with which they set the community ablaze.
</P>
<P>
The Ijaws also alleged that the Itsekiri people of their rival
community had hatched a plan to wear police and army uniforms to
attack the Ijaw people in both Warri and the riverine areas.
</P>
<P>
They accused the oil company of supporting the Itsekiri people
in the attacks, claiming further that helicopters belonging to
the company hovered over Ijaw locations before the attack.
</P>
<P>
They appealed to the state and federal governments to prevail
on the Itsekiri people to desist from further provoking them.
</P>
<P>
The communal clash started about four weeks ago with the Ijaws
protesting against the movement of the headquarters of the
newly-elected local government council from where they live to
another area inhabited by Itsekiri people.
</P>
<P>
They held hostage more than 170 oil workers and traders,
forcing the closure of nine crude oil flow stations belonging to
international oil giants Shell and Chevron.
</P>
<P>
Some shops and civilian property were burnt down during
ensuing riot there.
</P>
<P>
Both the state and federal governments have been involved in
the settlement of the issue while soldiers from the navy and and
police were sent to restore security.
</P>
<P>
The measures eased the tension about two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
So far no reports are available on what has been done to
settle the renewed communal clash, though Delta State
Administrator David Dungs has called on traditional rulers in the
state to assist in recovering all arms being held illegally by
citizens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
