<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, April 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The authorities of Saudi Arabia on Thursday
ruled out any deliberate starting of the fire disaster that
claimed the lives of more than 300 people and injured more than
2,000 others near the holy city of Mecca on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus in March plunged by
26.8 percent from a year earlier to 818.34 billion Japanese yen
(about 6.5 billion U.S. dollars) after rising in February for the
first time in 27 months, the Finance Ministry said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Zairean rebel leader Laurent Kabila left Cape
Town for home early on Thursday morning after meeting with South
African President Nelson Mandela, which had explored possible new
initiatives to end the civil war between Kabila's rebel force and
troops of Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko, said Mandela's
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- United States special Middle East coordinator
Dennis Ross, who arrived here Wednesday, is scheduled to meet
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu again on Thursday in an
effort to restart peace negotiations between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Defying mounting pressure on him to resign over
his alleged involvement in a political scandal, Israeli Prime
Minister Binyamin Netanyahu on Wednesday vowed to stay on to fight
for survival.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin signed a decree
Wednesday appointing Mikhail Fradkov minister of foreign economic
relations and trade, the presidential press service announced.
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- The Organization of Security and Cooperation in
Europe (OSCE) backed the intention of the Albanian government to
hold parliamentary elections due by the end of June, and will
provide aid for the polls, according to a statement made by the
OSCE special envoy on Wednesday. 
</P>
