<HEADLINE> Sino-Japanese Environmental Protection Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China and Japan will jointly
sponsor an environmental protection exhibition in Beijing this
October, to make the public more aware of the environment and the
country's strategy for sustained development.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition's organizer, the China Science and Technology
Museum, received 73,000 US dollars from the Japanese Government
this morning for the purpose.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony was held, with Zhou Guangzhao, chairman of the China
Association for Science and Technology, Ye Ruqiu, deputy director
of State Bureau of Environmental Protection, and representatives
of the Japanese Embassy present.
</P>
<P>
The donation came from the Japanese Government's "Grass-roots
Project", which supports small projects of community
organizations, and research and medical institutes in developing
nations.
</P>
<P>
Each donation is usually no more than 10 million yen. The
project has provided 152 million yen for 34 programs in China
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
Li Xiangyi, curator of the museum, said that the exhibition
will be held at the museum as part of activities marking the 25th
anniversary of the normalization of Sino-Japanese diplomatic
relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
