<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China's Drinking Water Project Fruitful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Clean drinking water is now
available to more than 48.5 million farmers in central China's
Hunan Province, or over 90 percent of the province's rural
population, according to the latest statistics.
</P>
<P>
Before the 1980s, the lack of sources of sanitary drinking
water posed a big problem in the province's rural areas. Many
farmers drank surface water directly from rivers, lakes and pools,
and in some southern and western mountainous areas people suffered
greatly from severe water shortages.
</P>
<P>
By 1985, some 60 percent of the farmers were still drinking
unclean water, according to statistics. As a result, the rate of
intestinal infectious disease and parasitosis remained alarmingly
high, with that of the dysentery coming to 2.2 per thousand and
that of the hepatitis 0.5 per thousand.
</P>
<P>
In a village in the province's southwestern part, 136 of the
148 families suffer from infectious hepatitis, sources say.
</P>
<P>
To solve the problem and protect people's health, the province
earmarked one million yuan for a rural drinking water clean-up
project in 1985. Over the past decade, a total of 440 million yuan
from the government and enterprises has been spent in the work.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary figures also reveal that local farmers have
contributed some 700 million yuan to the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
