<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gardeners Use Herbal Medicine to Treat Decaying Pine Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- From ancient times through the
present, traditional herbal medicine has been the cure of choice
in China for sick humans. Now, prescriptions are being given to
withering pine trees in the country's capital city.
</P>
<P>
Gardeners in an ancient temple in suburban Beijing have
successfully saved the lives of five pines, which each are more
than 1,300 years old, by using a mixture of herbal medicine,
according to a report in today's Beijing Daily.
</P>
<P>
The leaves of the trees in western Beijing's Jietai Temple
turned yellow in recent years, due to decay caused by their
inability to absorb nutrition through their thin bark. The trees
suffered from "malnutrition," the report quoted experts as saying.
</P>
<P>
To treat the trees, the gardeners hollowed out the dead wood
and stuffed the tree trunks with a preparation of 46 kinds of
herbal medicine.
</P>
<P>
Ren Wenshu, head of the management office of the temple, told
the newspaper that the temple has applied for the patent right for
the prescription.
</P>
<P>
The gardeners also replaced most of the trees' bark with
manmade bark in order to prevent rainwater from seeping into the
tree trunk.
</P>
<P>
Ren said they will re-treat the insides of the trees every two
to three years.
</P>
<P>
Jietai Temple, built in the year 622, is one of Beijing's
famous tourist attractions because of its ancient unusual-shaped
pines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Criticizes U.S. for Alleged Hostility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has attacked the United
States administration for its alleged hostility, the Zambia Daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
When meeting here on Wednesday with Arlene Render, U.S.
Ambassador to Zambia and Gerard Gallucci, visiting senior
official of the Sate Department, Zambian Minister Without
Portfolio Michael Sata said if the Zambian government was not
tactful, there could have been an uprising in his country
instigated by the United States through what he called
"undeclared sanctions".
</P>
<P>
The Zambian minister accused the U.S. of being biased against
Zambia, saying that "you have treated us with utmost political
hostility for the past few years through your undeclared
sanctions which have led to reduced levels of aid to Zambia."
</P>
<P>
The two U.S. officials called on Sata to exchange views on
Zambia's current political situation and seek ways to improve
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. officials told Sata that the U.S. will not relent on
its demands for good governance.
</P>
<P>
Gallucci expressed his dissatisfaction at Zambia's
constitutional changes.
</P>
<P>
Zambia held the general elections in November last year under
the changed constitution, which factually barred former president
Kenneth Kaunda from running for the presidency because his
parents are immigrants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
