<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Projects Play Vital Role in Ningxia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region,
an underdeveloped inland area in northwest China, completed a
dozen key projects last year, narrowing the gap between it and the
economically-developed coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
The lift-pump water system, which provides clean water to
millions of people and domestic animals in Shaanxi and Gansu
provinces and Ningxia, recently went into operation on a limited
basis.
</P>
<P>
The Lingwu Mine has opened, bringing an additional annual 1.5
million tons of coal; the third generating unit of Daba Power
Plant has connected with the power grid; and construction of the
Hedong Airport in Yinchuan and the Zhongwei Bridge across the
Yellow River have been completed.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia, one of the five autonomous regions inhabited by ethnic
groups in China, remains underdeveloped as a result of its harsh
climate, inarable land and lack of funds and technology.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the region has used World Bank loans to
build comprehensive agricultural projects which irrigated 50,000
ha of farmland and raised the grain output above two billion
kg. The output of meat, eggs, milk, fruit and aquatic products
increased at an annual rate of 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other key projects initiated in the region included power
plants, refineries, cement works, highway bridges and
telecommunication facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Farmers Change During Urbanization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- When Wu Cuidi, a villager in the
suburb of Shanghai, China's largest economic center, moved to
town, she tossed out all her old furniture and farm tools.
</P>
<P>
"Although they have been with me for decades, I have to do this
because the city lifestyle is different from that in the village,"
Wu said.
</P>
<P>
With the rapid growth of Shanghai's economy, the urbanization
of the city's neighboring rural areas has also grown more
quickly. Statistics show that some 1.8 million farmers have moved
to town, and 35 percent of the city's rural people now live in
more-populated areas. The figure takes the lead in the country.
</P>
<P>
To help the new city dwellers adapt to the urban environment,
all towns in the region have launched a campaign to promote
healthier and cleaner lifestyles, and have discouraged such habits
as littering and spitting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some of the new city dwellers have replaced their
old-fashioned farm tools and furniture with computers, pianos and
books. A number of residential areas have opened classes in
painting, music, and how-to courses for collecting antiques or
books. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
