The audit showed that, out of 1,012 inspections on various
bridges, spans, tunnels, culverts, earthworks, foundations and
other elements of the project, 3.8 percent or 39 were found to be
so defective as to require reconstruction, and 17.5 percent or 177
were needed to be repaired. Among these, five of the total 37
bridges were judged to have structural problems endangering safety.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. auditors said only 297 works, or 29.4 percent of the
total examined, were in "health," and another 148 inspections were
going to be done.
</P>
<P>
The substandard construction followed the collapse of a bridge
over the Han River, which claimed the lives of 32 people in 1994,
and another of a upscale department store in Seoul, which killed
more than 450 people in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The KIIRC said it would soon order the construction companies
involved to reconstruct or repair the rail though it would result
in cost overruns and delays in construction.
</P>
<P>
The 412-kilometer high-speed rail project, which was launched
by the KHRC in 1992, had been estimated to cost 12 billion dollars
and to be completed in 2002 as the world's fifth high-speed rail.
</P>
<P>
A KHRC official, who asked for anonymity, said the revised cost
would range between 20 billion to 22 billion dollars and the
completion would be delayed by three or four years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
