<HEADLINE> S. Korea Court Upholds Sentences for Former Presidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, April 17 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's Supreme Court upheld
today the life imprisonment for former President Chun Doo-hwan and
the 17-year jail term for his successor Roh Tae-woo for their
mutiny, treason and corruption.
</P>
<P>
In a plenary session, the Supreme Court rejected the
prosecution's appeal for a reexamination of the verdicts handed
down by the Seoul High Court in December.
</P>
<P>
Also endorsed was the lower court's decision to fine Chun an
equivalent of 248 million U.S. dollars and Roh 295 million dollars
for accepting bribes from business tycoons.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court also upheld the sentences on 12 former
generals for their roles in the 1980 Kwangju massacre, which
resulted in about 200 deaths. 
