<HEADLINE> Record Offshore Oil Output for First Quarter of Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- China pumped about 4.43 million
tons of offshore crude oil and 970 million cu m of gas in the
first three months of this year, up 31.6 percent and 57 percent,
respectively, over the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"This is a record quarterly output with average daily crude
output topping 49,100 tons," said a senior official with the China
National Offshore Oil Corp (CNOOC).
</P>
<P>
The CNOOC source said that the oil and gas output will be
further boosted this year, as a group of new oil and gas fields
are scheduled to be put into operation offshore before end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
These projects include the Xijiang 24-1 and the Lufeng 22-1 oil
fields in the South China Sea, the J block of Suizhong 36-1
oilfield and Boxi oilfield group in the Bohai Sea, as well as the
Jinzhou 20-2 gas field in the Bohai Sea's Liaodong Bay.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that CNOOC has entered its best period of
development, with all its 19 operational offshore oil and gas
fields producing rich turnouts.
</P>
<P>
He said the offshore oil and gas output this year is expected
to exceed that of 15 million tons and three billion cu m recorded
for 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
