<HEADLINE> Beijing to Host Asia's Largest Metal, Metallurgy Exposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The China 1997 International
Metal and Metallurgy Exposition, the largest of its kind in Asia,
is to be held May 8-12 here at the China International Exhibition
Center.
</P>
<P>
It is also believed to be the third largest of its kind
worldwide, following two similar shows, one held in Duesseldorf in
Germany, and another in Birmingham in Britain.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition is expected to draw more than 700 enterprises
from 26 countries and regions, including the US, Japan, Britain,
Germany, France, and Italy, with floor space for exhibits
exceeding 25,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Items on display will include up-to-date equipment and
technology used for metallurgical production and heat treatment,
and casting and forging products. More than 200
technology-exchange activities will be staged during the show.
</P>
<P>
It is the second time for China to hold such a large-scale
showcase event. The first was held in 1995, when separate shows
held by the China International Foundry, Forging, Industrial
Furnaces and Metallurgical Equipment Exhibition and the China
Metallurgical Industry exposition, were combined.
</P>
<P>
The show is co-sponsored by the Ministry of Metallurgical
Industry, the Ministry of Machine-Building Industry and the China
Council for the Promotion of International Trade.
</P>
<P>
China led the world in producing some 100 million tons of steel
in 1996. In addition, its iron and steel industry has
achieved remarkable success in restructuring industrial setup,
improving products and adding varieties, reducing energy
consumption, and lifting economic returns.
</P>
<P>
During the 1996-2000 period, the industry gives priority to
developing new varieties and improving products by helping its
enterprises upgrade technology and equipment.
</P>
<P>
The country has also witnessed a speedy growth in its heat
processing industry, with output of foundry goods rising from less
than 10 million tons in 1990 to around 12 million tons in 1995 and
output of forged parts from 1.8 million tons to 2.2 million
tons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
