<HEADLINE> Northwest China To Support Itself in Grain Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China will add another
four million tons of grain to its granary by the end of the
century, to ensure grain self-sufficiency and provide more for the
state.
</P>
<P>
The area produced a record grain output of 32 million tons last
year, six million tons more than the previous year. But it still
faces grain shortages.
</P>
<P>
The area includes the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, the
Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region, and Gansu, Qinghai, and Shaanxi
provinces. It has a population of 80 million and has to import
nearly 400,000 tons of grain annually.
</P>
<P>
Northwest China gives top priority to grain production and has
invested 10 billion yuan into building irrigation works over the
past few years.
</P>
<P>
To combat droughts, the area initiated rainwater storage wells,
500,000 of which have contributed greatly to grain growth.
Agro-sciences are also proving successful: Gansu Province applied
plastic sheeting technique to about 183,000 ha of grain last year
and recorded a per-hectare yield of 6,900 kg.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang is trying to win state approval and support for a
water and soil development project, which will cost 10 billion
yuan to reclaim nearly 670,000 ha of wasteland, to gain an
additional five billion cubic meters of water resources and five
million more tons of grain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
