<HEADLINE> Retired Chinese Teacher Launches Tree Planting Movement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A 71-year-old man in east China's
Fujian Province has spent the past 10 years covering a barren hill
with trees and is determined to reclaim more than six ha of barren
hillsides during his remaining years.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Qinmao, a retired teacher, began his green campaign in
1987 when he retired and returned to his hometown of Longxiang
Village.
</P>
<P>
He knew the village's history too well to bear the bleak
sight. The forest resources there had been destroyed for one
reason or another, but the old man made up his mind to turn the
hillsides green.
</P>
<P>
Day and night, he set about cutting weeds and working on the
wasteland, eating rations in the field and drinking col water.
The sun burned his skin and he took shelter from the rain in his
work shed.
</P>
<P>
But, ten years of hard work and over 50,000 yuan in investment
paid off. An 8.6 hectare fruit garden is taking shape on the
hills, and his "green capital" is 120,000 yuan-worth.
</P>
<P>
He has planted fir and fruit trees and has begun to breed
poultry and livestock with the help of experts. He earned more
than 20,000 yuan last year, in addition to his pension.
</P>
<P>
The ex-teacher is ready to share his experiences with neighbors
and resume his teaching, but this time about how to plant trees
and raise animals. He is even providing nursery stocks for the
needy and can help them have a better life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
