<HEADLINE> North China's Anti-Illiteracy Drive Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- By the end of last year, 600,000
young people and adults in north China's Shanxi Province were
illiterate, representing only two percent of the province's total
population, according to the lastest statistics.
</P>
<P>
Shanxi has worked energetically to wipe out illiteracy since
the establishment of the People's Republic of China in
1949. Figures show that about 600,000 young people and adults
overcame illiteracy during the 1977-1987 period, and the
illiteracy rate dropped to 15.97 percent during the ten years.
</P>
<P>
The State Council, China's highest governing body, issued a
decree in 1988 to form a legal framework for the country's
anti-illiteracy campaign.
</P>
<P>
In early 1990, Shanxi reviewed the illiteracy situation among
young people and adults, and updated its records. Meanwhile, it
gave priority to the poor areas and to young people and adults,
and increased supervision over the work.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 98 percent of the towns and 60 percent of
the villages throughout the province have opened night schools for
adults, and some one million people have received tecknical
training.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
