<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Falls in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus
in March plunged by 26.8 percent from a year earlier to 818.34
billion Japanese yen (about 6.5 billion U.S. dollars) after rising
in February for the first time in 27 months, the Finance Ministry
said today.
</P>
<P>
The monthly data shows overall import growth has been far
outpacing export expansion, but "the tempo of decline of Japan's
trade surplus is slowing down, as the export growth has marked
double-digit rate for the past several months," the ministry said
in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Of Japan's global trade in March, exports increased by 10.5
percent to 4,540.77 billion yen (36.3 billion dollars), while
imports totaled 3,722.43 billion yen (29.8 billion dollars), up
24.4 percent from a year earlier.  
</P>
</TEXT>
