<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 07:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ross Continues Shuttle Mission in Mideast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 17 (Xinhua) -- United States special Middle
East coordinator Dennis Ross, who arrived here Wednesday, is
scheduled to meet Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu again
today in an effort to restart peace negotiations between Israel
and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Later today, Ross, who met Netanyahu Wednesday before traveling
to Gaza for talks with Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
President Yasser Arafat, will also meet Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy and Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai.
</P>
<P>
Ross is reportedly trying to hammer out a formula which will
get the two sides back to the negotiating table and end the
crisis which erupted with Israel's decision to start construction
of settlement in Har Homa in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
After a half-hour meeting with Netanyahu Wednesday, Ross said
that a way has to be found to put the peace process back on track
and to ensure that violence is not going to be part of it.
</P>
<P>
"We also have to find a way to move the process forward
in a way which ensures that the hopes of each side can
be realized and that we have a credible negotiating process,"
said Ross.
</P>
<P>
The two did not discuss the proposal to advance the final
status talks between Israel and the Palestinians, or the second
pullback of the Israeli army from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made it clear to Ross that only the cessation
of terrorism would lead to the resumption of the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Arafat and Levy agreed Wednesday to revive peace
talks, at a meeting staged by the European Union (EU) at the
EU-Mediterranean conference in Malta, and both of them declared a
renewed readiness to seek peace.
</P>
<P>
For its part, the EU hailed their meeting as a crowning
achievement after years of aiming to achieve a more significant
role for Europe in the U.S.-led peace process in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Arafat's spokesman, Marwan Kanafani, said the Palestinian
leader and Levy promised to "go back to the peace process."
</P>
<P>
However, Kanafani denied reports that Arafat agreed to renew
security coordination, saying "We have no direct coordination
except through the American side since Mr. Netanyahu ended
political coordination." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Folk Artist Hails Return of Hong Kong With Paper-cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 17 (Xinhua) -- A young artist in north China's
Shanxi Province has hailed the return of Hong Kong to China with a
pair of scissors.
</P>
<P>
Li Binjie, 32, spent more than a year cutting 100 dragons out
of a 56-m scroll of paper and cloth. He explained that the numeral
56 signifies the 56 ethnic groups in China welcoming the return of
Hong Kong; 100 stands for the return of Hong Kong after 100 years
of separation from the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Li hoped that the paper-cut, known to be the largest of its
kind in the world, will be included in the Guinness Book of World
Records and put on display in Hong Kong on July 1 when China
resumes the sovereignty over the territory.
</P>
<P>
Li is now a cadre of the Tungsten Filament Factory in Xinzhou
Prefecture. Born in the countryside in northern Shanxi, where
paper-cutting is a popular folk art, he has been engaged in making
paper-cuts for a dozen years. He is now a member of the China
Research Society of Paper-cuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
