<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kabila Ends Talks With Mandela, Returning Home </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Zairean rebel leader
Laurent Kabila left Cape Town for home early this morning while
South African President Nelson Mandela said he was "satisfied"
with their closed-door talks held Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's spokesman Joel Netshitenzhe told a press conference
that the talks had explored possible new initiatives to end the
civil war between Kabila's rebel force and troops of Zairean
President Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
However, the meeting, which was expected to continue late into
the night, only lasted for 45 minutes. Kabila's representatives
still remained in the city, together with United Nations
special envoy Mohamed Sahnoun.
</P>
<P>
Officials close to the talks did not expect Mandela to take
part in any further talks, which might go ahead later today. But
they said the face-to-face peace talks between Kabila and Mobutu
could soon be effected.
</P>
<P>
In Kinshasa, Zairean Information Minister Kin-Kiey Mulumba
said Mobutu and his arch-rival could meet directly once their
envoys had consulted in Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
"Things are getting clearer. Plans are afoot for a meeting
between the head of state and the rebel leader. This meeting is
imminent," Kin-Kiey said.
</P>
<P>
Mandela has been hoping to bring Mobutu and Kabila together in
South Africa as part of his efforts to make peace in Zaire.
</P>
<P>
Kabila arrived in Cape Town from Zaire's second city of
Lubumbashi which had been seized by rebels last week after only
token resistance from Mobutu's troops. The rebels so far have
controlled about half of the mine-rich central African country.
</P>
<P>
Despite his willingness to hold peace talks with Mobutu's
government, Kabila dampened hopes for stopping rebel attacks of
capital Kinshasa, home to five million people.
</P>
<P>
"There will be no ceasefire until Mobutu relinquishes power,"
he told a mass rally in Lubumbashi, responding a ceasefire call
from U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
