<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus Falls in March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus
in March plunged by 26.8 percent from a year earlier to 818.34
billion Japanese yen (about 6.5 billion U.S. dollars) after rising
in February for the first time in 27 months, the Finance Ministry
said today.
</P>
<P>
The monthly data shows overall import growth has been far
outpacing export expansion, but "the tempo of decline of Japan's
trade surplus is slowing down, as the export growth has marked
double-digit rate for the past several months," the ministry said
in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
Of Japan's global trade in March, exports increased by 10.5
percent to 4,540.77 billion yen (36.3 billion dollars), while
imports totaled 3,722.43 billion yen (29.8 billion dollars), up
24.4 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
Japan's trade surplus last month with the United States
expanded 11.2 percent from a year earlier to 379.83 billion yen
(three billion dollars), the sixth consecutive monthly rise, amid
strong exports of automobile and office equipment, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, surpluses with the European Union (EU) and Asia
declined, due partly to the growing imports of liquefied natural
gas and telecommunication equipment, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The surplus with the EU fell by 39.2 percent to 131.29 billion
yen (1.1 billion dollars) and that with Asian countries went down
by 17.9 percent to 634.51 billion yen (5.1 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
However, some economists predicted that Japan's trade surplus
will turn upward in April as its industry will boost exports to
compensate for the decline of domestic consumption, which has been
brought about by the consumption tax hike from April 1.
</P>
<P>
In fiscal 1996, which ended on March 31, Japan's merchandise
trade surplus fell 29.6 percent to 6,421.25 billion yen (51
billion dollars), the fourth consecutive yearly decline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
