<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Rules Out Deliberate Starting of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The authorities of Saudi
Arabia ruled out any deliberate starting of the fire disaster
that claimed the lives of more than 300 people and injured more
than 2,000 others near the holy city of Mecca Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to reports from Saudi Arabia today, the kingdom
announced late Wednesday that initial investigations indicated
that the fire was an accident, which had no political
implications, official Saudi media reports quoted an official
statement as saying.
</P>
<P>
The fire in Mena was sparked by a gas canister used for
cooking, and strong winds made the fire sweep quickly across the
pilgrims camp of 70,000 tents. It took more than three hours to
put it out.
</P>
<P>
Most of the victims were reportedly Indians, besides
Pakistanis and Bangladeshis. An official announcement of the
nationalities of the victims is yet to be made.
</P>
<P>
The death toll Wednesday reached 343 as more bodies were
found from the debris where thick smell of smoke was still
pervasive in the air, and some seriously-wounded victims
succumbed to injuries.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said 217 people were confirmed dead and
more than 2,000 others injured in the fire.
</P>
<P>
The identification of victims is being hampered by the
charred state of many bodies, the Saudi authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The process of identifying the victims would begin in earnest
Friday after the end of the pilgrimage, as the Saudi authorities
were preoccupied with ensuring the smooth-running of the Haj
which reached its climax Wednesday as the two million pilgrims
came to Mount Arafat to mark the peak of the pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
The Haj authorities had intensified their efforts to ensure a
smooth movement of the pilgrims from Mena to Arafat Wednesday
following the fire.
</P>
<P>
The injured pilgrims who had been rushed to 12 nearby
hospitals and specialized medical centers after the fire were
receiving treatment with scores still being in critical
condition, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
