<HEADLINE> Indian Industry to Grow By 11 Percent: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- the Asian Development Bank
(ADB) said on Wednesday that it expected the Indian industry to
grow by a robust 11.7 percent in the financial years of 1997-98
(April-March) and 1998-99, the Times of India said today.
</P>
<P>
Industry will continue to be an engine of economic growth in
India, ADB said in its annual report on India.
</P>
<P>
The services sector, which accounts for more than 40 percent of
the Gross Domestic Product (GDP), is expected to grow by around
6.5 percent during this period, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
ADB said that since agriculture is an important contributor to
GDP growth, monsoons will continue to play an important role.
</P>
<P>
The bank suggested that GDP growth would be sustained at 7.0
percent in the next two years if the monsoon rains were favorable.
</P>
<P>
But the bank said inadequate infrastructure is an area of
concern.
</P>
<P>
"Expansion in the power generation industry slowed considerably
in 1996-97, and this may hold back future industrial growth as it
did in the past, it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank pointed out that the private sector must be encouraged
to take long-term stakes in infrastructure development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
