<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 07:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Vows not to Resign Despite Police Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Defying mounting pressure on
him to resign over his alleged involvement in a political
scandal, Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu has vowed to stay
on to fight for survival.
</P>
<P>
Following the revelation by state television Channel I
Wednesday evening that police investigators probing the so-called
"Bar-On for Hebron" scandal had recommended indicting Netanyahu
and three other key government figures, Netanyahu held urgent
consultations with his lawyer Yaakov Weinroth and senior aides
to discuss the implications.
</P>
<P>
The police reportedly recommended State Attorney Edada Arbel
and current Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein to charge
Netanyahu, Justice Minister Tzahi Hanegbi and Director-General of
the Prime Minsiter's Office Avigdor Liberman with breach of
trust and fraud for their roles in the scandal.
</P>
<P>
Police also recommended indicting Shas party leader Aryeh
Deri for blackmailing in pushing for the appointment of former
Jerusalem lawyer Roni Baron as the attorney-general in January.
</P>
<P>
Channel I reporter Ayala Hasson, who first broke the news
on the Bar-On scandal later January, said Deri conditioned
Shas' support of the Hebron deal on Bar-On's appointment,
because Bar-On promised to grant him a favorable plea bargin
in his bribery trial. Bar-On resigned two days after his
January 10 appointment only due to the public criticism of
his political affiliation and inadequate qualification for the
powerful position.
</P>
<P>
In reaction to the Channel I's latest report, Netanyahu's
spokesman Shai Bazak said the prime minister believed he would
have no problem with the affair and would "emerge spotless."
The Prime Minister's Office also accused the police's move of
being politically-motivated and intended to bring down the
government.
</P>
<P>
The reports about the police charges against Netanyahu
dropped a political bombshell in Israel, because this is the
first time in its history that a prime minister has been
charged by the police. Netanyahu was questioned late February
under caution by the police for his role in the Bar-On
appointment, and reportedly did not cooperate with his
investigators.
</P>
<P>
Many have begun to doubt the credibility of Netanyahu to
continue leading the government, while the main opposition Labor
party wasted no time in calling for his immediate resignation
to pave the way for new elections.
</P>
<P>
Labor leader Shimon Peres, who had been pushing for the
formation of a unity government with the Likud before the
reports about the police findings, said Wednesday that he no
longer continued his efforts and called for Netanyahu's
immediate resignation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a party rally in Tel Aviv Wednesday, leading
contender for the Labor leadership Ehud Barak demanded Netanyahu
and "ministers with a conscience" resign immediately. He dubbed
the Netanyahu government as "corrupt", saying it should be
"brought down, the sooner the better."
</P>
<P>
Another Labor leadership candidate Yossi Beilin urged the
Labor to launch "an unequivocal public campaign against the
prime minister, with the aim of bringing him down."
</P>
<P>
Meretz leader Yossi Sarid demanded, even before the
revelation of police charges against Netanyahu, Netanyahu and
Hanegbi resign now in order to pave the way for new
elections.
</P>
<P>
Even some ministers within the Likud-led coalition have also
made it clear that it would be the end of the government
if the state prosecution decided to endorse the police
recommendations to charge Netanyahu and the three others.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said that even if the attorney-general and
state attorney decided not to indict Netanyahu because of
insufficient evidence, serious damage has already been inflicted
on his government and the opposition can rely on the public
opinion to intensify its campaign to bring it down.
</P>
<P>
However, all will become clear about the fate of the
Netanyahu government within the next two or three days, during
which the State Attorney's Office is expected to announce its
decision on the police recommendations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
