<HEADLINE> Intl Conference to Be Held on Endangered Species </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 17 (Xinhua) -- About 3,000 delegates are
expected to attend the 12-day meeting of the Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES) to start in
Zimbabwe's capital Harare on June 9.
</P>
<P>
The meeting would be held amid calls from Zimbabwe and other
southern African countries for CITES to allow sustainable use of
wildlife, particularly easing the trade ban of African elephants.
</P>
<P>
They have been calling for downlisting of African elephants
from the convention's Appendix I, where trade is banned, to
Appendix II, which permits trade under strict controls for the
sale of the existing stockpile.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Zimbabwe has a 40 tons of ivory stockpile.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local daily "the Herald" quoted a spokesman for the
Ministry of Environment and Tourism as saying that preparations
for the international conference were at "an advanced stage".
</P>
<P>
Up to 138 countries are expected to send representatives to
the meeting, while almost 700 journalist, both local and foreign,
are expected to cover the conference.
</P>
<P>
Adequate accommodation for delegates has been secured, with 11
hotels in Harare already block booked for the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0233 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Can Realize 8 Percent Growth: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia can realize
economic growth of more than 8 percent for the next five to 10
years if Total Factor Productivity (TFP) contributed at least 30
percent to the targeted overall productivity growth of six
percent, according to the 1996 Productivity Report released by the
National Productivity Center today.
</P>
<P>
The report said in order to achieve the contribution level, the
TFP must grow at a minimum of two percent a year.
</P>
<P>
For the 1987-96 period, the average growth in the TFP was 1.7
percent with Capital Intensity growing at 5.9 percent, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report said the main source of Capital Intensity growth was
capital which contributed 65 percent to the overall productivity
growth of 4.7 percent, while TFP contributed 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the manufacturing sector continued to
be the major contributor (48 percent) to the overall productivity
growth. The other main contributor was the Aggregate Services
comprising Commerce/Trade (15.2 percent), Finance (13.2 percent)
and Transport (13 percent).
</P>
<P>
The combined contribution by the Manufacturing and Aggregate
Services sectors to overall growth was 89.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report said manufacturing maintained its position as one of
the leading sectors of the economy, with productivity growth of
5.8 percent, employment growth of 6.6 percent and output growth of
12.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report said that to enhance TFP, there is a need to shift
economic growth from input-driven towards productivity-driven, as
emphasized in the Seventh Malaysia Plan (1996-2000) and the Second
Industrial Master Plan (1996-2005). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
