<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Third Guyana Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) today approved the third annual loan for Guyana under
the Enhanced Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF).
</P>
<P>
The loan, equivalent to about 24 million U.S. dollars, is
provided in support of the Guyana government's economic program in
1997.
</P>
<P>
The loan is available in two biannual installments, the first
of which will be available on April 30.
</P>
<P>
In the major macroeconomic objectives of the 1997 economic
program, the Guyana government will increase the gross domestic
product (GDP) by seven percent, lower the annual inflation rate to
four percent by the end of the year and limit the deterioration of
the current account deficit to about 12 percent of GDP.
</P>
<P>
Guyana joined the IMF in September, 1966. Its quota is about 92
million dollars equivalent, and its outstanding use of IMF
financing currently totals about 151 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ESAF is a concessional IMF facility for assisting eligible
member countries that are undertaking economic reform programs to
strengthen their balance of payments and improve their growth
prospects. The loans carry an interest rate of 0.5 percent a year
and are repayable over 10 years, with a five-and-half- year grace
period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Needs New Economic Strategies: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia should emphasize
productivity-driven growth initiatives to keep its growth
sustainable in the long term, according to the 1996 Productivity
Report (PR) released here today by the government National
Productivity Center.
</P>
<P>
The report said that as Malaysia's growth, which is mainly
input-driven, may not be sustainable in the long run, it is
necessary to put stress on productivity-driven growth initiatives.
</P>
<P>
"Improvements in the TFP will lead to increased productivity
and enable the economy to generate a larger output from the same
available resources. Hence, shifting to a higher growth path," it
said.
</P>
<P>
It has outlined three major strategies to enhance Malaysia's
Total Factor Productivity (TFP) to transform the country's growth
strategy from input-driven to productivity-driven.
</P>
<P>
The first is to upgrade local expertise in the field of
productivity and quality (P&AMP;Q). This will involve intensifying P&AMP;Q
training programs and management systems development to upgrade
knowledge and skills of employees and improve management systems.
</P>
<P>
Another strategy would be improving input for policy
formulation and planning to enhance P&AMP;Q. This calls for the
development of databases on productivity indicators at the
sectoral, national and international levels for industries.
</P>
<P>
Besides, this strategy also identifies the need to conduct
research on current issues in P&AMP;Q to ensure that updated data and
information are made available to industries.
</P>
<P>
The third strategy, for promoting greater awareness and
practices of P&AMP;Q systems of management and work culture, stresses
the importance of promotional activities in the area of P&AMP;Q
management.
</P>
<P>
The report said that in order to effectively implement the
plans to enhance TFP growth, information on productivity and
quality must be widely disseminated to everyone concerned.
</P>
<P>
For this purpose, it said, a three-year National Productivity
Enhancement campaign should be undertaken to hasten the shift to
more value-added activities through capital- and
technology-intensive production processes and to enhance global
competitiveness through technology development and market
expansion.
</P>
<P>
The report called for a more significant role for the private
sector in technology acquisition and transfer as well as
commercialization in the field of research and development to
ensure sustained and competitive industrial technology
development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
