<HEADLINE> Airlines Agree to Install Collision Avoidance System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Most domestic and international
carriers operating in India have agreed to install airborne
collision avoidance system (ACAS) in their aircraft as per the
schedule recommended by the Indian Civil Aviation Ministry.
</P>
<P>
According to the Hindustan Times today, Director General of
Civil Aviation H.S. Khola confirmed on Wednesday that the civil
aviation authorities of neighboring countries have also approved
the move.
</P>
<P>
Installation of ACAS by all aircraft would improve air safety
and the move is a right step in view of the increasing traffic and
congestion of air corridors, Khola said at a press conference held
here.
</P>
<P>
Two aircraft, including one Boeing 747 from the Saudi Airlines,
collided mid-air over India's Haryana state on November 12 last
year, killing about 350 people. 
</P>
