<HEADLINE> Kidnaping Drops in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Kidnaping dropped by 6.9
percent in the first quarter of this year compared with a year
earlier, a government report published today said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 334 kidnaping cases, 124 or 37 percent, were committed
by the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Paramilitary groups and the People's Liberation Army also
carried out kidnapings, according to the report by the National
Anti-kidnaping Council of the army, the Anti-kidnaping Division of
the police and the Free Country Foundation.
</P>
<P>
Children under 18 were the favorite targets of the kidnapers, which
accounted for 12.3 percent of the kidnapings, to be followed by
merchants, ranchers, engineers, farmers and doctors.
</P>
<P>
The provinces of Antioquia and Cesar reported the highest
number of kidnapings with 46 cases each. Next on the list were
Valle del Cauca, Choco and Sucre.
</P>
<P>
The report said that more than 333 million U.S. dollars ransom
were demanded in the first quarter of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
