<HEADLINE> Czech Republic Adopts New Economic Measures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Czech government adopted a
package of new measures today in efforts to improve the country's
ailing economic situation.
</P>
<P>
A document on economic policy adjustment and transition
measures was adopted by the government after heated debates.
</P>
<P>
It requested the government to reduce the country's budget by 5
percent to 25.5 billion koruny (880 million U.S. dollars), control
salary increase, promote exports and reduce imports.
</P>
<P>
The measures also include privatization of state-run
enterprises, promotion of the financial market and strengthened
combat against economic crime.
</P>
<P>
The measures were designed to improve economic performance. The
growth rate of the gross domestic product (GDP) dropped from 4.8
percent in 1995 to 4.4 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit rose to 8.5 billion koruny (300 million
dollars) in the first quarter of this year, and its trade deficit
that was 160.3 billion koruny (5.5 billion dollars) in 1996 is
expected to grow to 220 billion koruny (7.6 billion dollars) this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
