<HEADLINE> Nepal to Grant Export License for Hydropower Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government is ready
to grant permission to a hydropower project to be developed by a
foreign company for exporting its electricity to neighboring
India, the local press said today.
</P>
<P>
Talks on the export license for the West Seti project in
far-west Nepal between the authorities and Australia's Snowy
Mountain Engineering Corp. have come to the final stage, reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Nepali Water Resources Ministry said the
export permission will be soon granted so that the Australian
company could start formal negotiations with prospective power
buyers in India at an early date.
</P>
<P>
The 750-megawatt West Seti project, at an estimated cost of
over 1 billion U.S. dollars, is Nepal's first hydropower project
entirely promoted for electricity export.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Snowy Mountain had held extensive discussions with
electricity authorities of northern Indian states, some of which
have expressed their intentions to buy power from the project,
company sources said.
</P>
<P>
An Indian research institute estimated last year that India's
northern region will face a power shortage of at least 21,000
megawatts in the next 15 years.
</P>
<P>
Nepali officials said the construction of the project, located
near Nepal's border with India, would begin soon after the
Australian developer finalizes power deals with Indian buyers.
</P>
<P>
The project, also the country's first totally promoted by
foreign investors, is closely watched as a testing ground by other
prospective foreign investors of Nepal's abundant water resources,
they said.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government has adopted a policy to boost the
country's economic growth through encouraging foreign investment
in the hydropower sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
