<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Myanmar's Communications Sector Experiences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has made greater strides
in developing its communications sector, according to official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
The number of telephones in Myanmar reached 168,399 in the
1995-96 fiscal year, up from 73,545 at the beginning of the 1990s
when it was difficult to make trunk calls in the country.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar began introducing the auto-telephone system in 1958 and
there were only four auto-exchange stations then in Yangon,
capital of Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
The latest official figures indicate that 78 auto-exchange
stations (AES) and 410 conventional exchange stations (CES) in 14
states and divisions have been set up by the end of February this
year, up from the 33 AES and 210 CES in 1988.
</P>
<P>
During the last four-year plan period from 1992-93 to 1995-96,
some 7,000 auto-exchange lines were installed in Myanmar's three
cities -- Bago, Taunggyi and Dawei. The number of towns, which
have auto telephones, increased to 53 by the end of fiscal 1995-96
from 29 in fiscal 1990-91.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, 2,000 cellular phones were installed during
the plan period in Yangon and 1,000 more is being installed in
Mandalay, the second largest city of the country.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's telecommunications services are run by the government
as the sole agent.
</P>
<P>
However, a number of foreign companies have been involved in
the installation of communications systems in Myanmar on contracts
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
These foreign firms, mainly from Australia, Israel, Germany,
Japan, Singapore and the United States, are going to set up a
20,000 auto-radio telephone system and install over 4,000 cellular
phones throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has introduced a micro-wave link system to ensure
smooth and direct trunk calls with major towns of the border
regions.
</P>
<P>
The digital micro-wave link connecting Mandalay with the other
five cities -- Pyin Oo Lwin, Lashio, Loikaw, Shwebo and Pakokku --
has been successfully launched one after another since September
last year.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of the micro-wave link system signified that
Myanmar's communications sector has entered into a new stage of
development.
</P>
<P>
And the rapid development of the country's communications
sector will in turn facilitate the country's economic development
and help induce foreign investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economy Predicted to Grow at 7 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's economy will grow at
7 percent a year in the 1996-2000 period, an economic expert said.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth is possible because all the elements for it
are present in Indonesia, Prof. Anwar Nasution said here Wednesday
when launching of an annual report issued by the United Nations'
Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
Entitled Economic and Social Survey of Asia and the Pacific
1997, the report said that Indonesia has experienced very rapid
change in the structure of its production, with a decline in the
share of agriculture in gross domestic product (GDP) from 31
percent to 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, the percentage of the labor force in agriculture
remains as high as 55 percent, said the report.
</P>
<P>
As between industry and services, the share of services is
higher, although it has experienced a rapid rate of industrial
growth since 1980.
</P>
<P>
It held that this imbalance between the sectoral share of
output and employment is a source of continuing concern, as it
reflects a rise in the disparity between the income levels of the
urban industrial sector and the rural agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
The report also mentioned that Indonesia's economic growth has
been supported by high rates of domestic investment and savings.
</P>
<P>
Domestic investment rose to around 40 percent of GDP in 1995,
from 30 percent in 1990. Thus, investment has been financed
largely by domestic saving, which reached 36 percent of GDP or
more in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has experienced a stable average inflation rate of
about 8.5 percent since 1981.
</P>
<P>
Regarding Indonesia's foreign trade, the report mentioned that
the rate of growth of exports has accelerated sharply between
1985-1989 and 1990-1995 from 0.9 percent to 12.7 percent per year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0263 </DOCNO>
