<HEADLINE> Argentina: Unhappy With U.S. Action on Argentine Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Argentina is unhappy with
the action taken by the United States which removed 130 Argentine
products from the preferential tariff system, Julio Caceres,
Argentine Economy Minister's coordinating secretary, said here
today.
</P>
<P>
In the belief that Argentina has not taken adequate and
efficient measures to protect intellectual property rights, the
U.S. government announced Tuesday it would remove Argentine
products from the preferential tariff treatment.
</P>
<P>
This will bring to Argentina a loss of 260 million U.S. dollars
in exports, Caceres estimated.
</P>
<P>
Argentina would take the case to international organizations,
including the World Trade Organization, he said, adding that it
has already been brought to the legislative bodies to decide
whether to ban U.S. companies from bidding for contracts here.
</P>
<P>
However, on Tuesday, Argentine Foreign Minister Guido di Tella
issued a statement, saying despite the fact that the U.S. measures
constitute a blow to Argentina, it will not be modify its present
patent law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
