<HEADLINE> Belarussian President Calls for Non-nuclear Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 19 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian President Alexandr
Lukashenko today reiterated his objection to the eastwards
expansion of the North Atlatic Treaty Organization (NATO), and called for
the building of a non-nuclear zone in eastern and central Europe.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a symposium on economic development in Minsk,
Lukashenko said that instead of bringing stability in Europe,
NATO's expansion would only prove detrimental to stability.
</P>
<P>
Belarus had experienced some of the worst warfare this century,
and that was the reason why it was against the expansion, he said.
</P>
<P>
The alliance has been actively seeking to invite some former
Warsaw Pact bloc countries to join the organization. Among the
front-runners are Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of building a non-nuclear zone in eastern and
central Europe, which was initiated by himself, Lukashenko said
this was not a vacant political slogan, but a call from the
"hearts of the Belarussian people."
</P>
<P>
So far, China and Russia have backed the non-nuclear proposal,
while most Western countries remained indifferent. 
</P>
