<HEADLINE> Mobiline Philippine Golf Open Fires Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGUIO CITY, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The 82nd Mobiline Philippine
Golf Open, one of the 12-stop 1996-1997 Asian Tour, teed off here
on Wednesday at Camp John Hay in the northern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
A total of 141 entries from 15 countries and regions, including
the United States, England and host the Philippines, have
confirmed their participation in the four-day par 68 event.
</P>
<P>
The tournament, organized by the Philippine Golf Association
and conducted by the Asian Pacific Golf Confederation, staked
money prizes of 300,000 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Reigning champion Rob Whidock of Australia is not around to
defend his title, but Briton Edward Fryatt, 26, currently No. 1 in
the 1996-97 Asian Tour Order of Merit, will compete with some top
players in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
Other top golfers who are seeing action Wednesday include
American Gary Rusnak, Larry Barber, Kevin Wenthworth and Tim
Straub, who are ranking No. 2, No. 3, No. 8 and No. 18
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Takao Nogami and Yasuharu Imano, winners in the
recently concluded Mitsubishi Motors-Southwoods Open in Manila and
Konica-UBX Manila Open, are also participating. The two shotmakers
rank No. 7 and No. 16 in the Order of Merit.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines constitutes the bulk of the entries with 66
golfers including Rodrigo Cuelio, the No. 4 in the Order of Merit,
Frankie Minoza and Danny Zarate, the No. 1 in the local circult.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Open, which turns 82 this year, is one of the oldest
golf championships in Asia. Its occurance in the summer capital of
the Philippines marks for the first time that the country's golf
spectacle was held in the North since 1913.
</P>
<P>
As a warm-up for the Philippine Open, a professional-amateur
tournament was played Tuesday. Cap-2 led by local professional
Roger Diocares won th team event, scoring an impressive victory of
112 (62-50) under the four-to-play, two-to-count format.
</P>
<P>
Ull Zilg of Germany, who ranks No. 58 in the Order of Merit,
beat all individual players with 3-under-par 85 (34-31). However,
Fryatt Scored 74, expecting to play better on Wednesday. 
