<HEADLINE> Mercosur Demands US Elimination of Import Duties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Southern Common Market
(Mercosur) insisted today that the United States eliminate its
import duties before negotiating tariff reductions that will lead
to a Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA).
</P>
<P>
This stand was put forth by Jose Alfredo Graza Lima, the
economic department chief of Brazil's Foreign Ministry, during the
third meeting of deputy trade ministers from the American
continent.
</P>
<P>
Graza Lima said that the members of the Mercosur, formed by
Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay, prefer that the United
State eliminate its trade barriers and that tariff reductions be
discussed as of the year 2003.
</P>
<P>
Peter Allgeier, head of the U.S. delegation, proposed that the
American countries begin tariff negotiations and other points
related to market access in 1998 so that the FTAA can be
established in the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
There has been a broader pan-American effort to negotiate by
2005 a Canada-to-Chile Free Trade Area of the Americas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
