<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OSCE Backs Albanian Election Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of Security and
Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) backs the intention of the Albanian
government to hold parliamentary elections due by the end of June,
and will provide aid for the polls.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made today by Franc Vranicki, the visiting
special envoy of the OSCE, in Tirana.
</P>
<P>
Vranicki made the remarks during talks with Albanian Prime
Minister Bashkim Fino, one day after the Italian-led multinational
force started its operations in Albania.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Albanian prime minister's office said
the two sides mainly discussed the preparatory work for the polls,
cooperation between the multinational force and the Albanian
authorities, and promotion of political dialogue with various
parties in Albania.
</P>
<P>
"The fruitful talks will be conducive to working out a
strategic plan for stabilizing the Albanian situation and the
multinational force's operation in the country," it added.
</P>
<P>
Fino noted at the talks that it was imperative to hold the
elections on the time fixed by the political parties through
discussion. Otherwise, the situation would be complicated.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people have been killed in recent unrest in
Albania sparked by the collapse of popular pyramid savings schemes
last December.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Security Council passed a resolution on
March 25 authorizing the dispatch of a 6,000-member, Italian-led
multinational force for three months to protect relief operations
in Albania.
</P>
<P>
About 1,200 Italian, French and Spanish soldiers landed in
Albania on Tuesday and began to take control of harbors, airports
and other main communication facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
