<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila's Exit From IMF Good for Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The scheduled exit of the
Philippines from the International Monetary Fund (IMF) supervision
this year will mean more business for the country, local newspaper
the Philippine Journal said today.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines' planned exit from the IMF will give the
country a clean bill of health and raise its credit rating to an
investment grade, Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo was quoted
as telling a meeting of businessmen Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
One of the most significant implications of this event will be
the ability of the government as well Filipino-owned business
enterprises to gain access to the financial markets that offer
cheap and low-interest loans, de Ocampo said.
</P>
<P>
De Ocampo said the scheduled exit will take effect by the end
of this June despite the delays in the passage of the proposed
Comprehensive Tax Reform Package which remains pending in the
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines' economic development has been under the IMF's
supervision for about 35 years. With its economy growing with
unprecedented rates in recent years, the Philippines has sought to
get free from the IMF.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
