<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Plant to Treat Ship Sewage Operational </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The water quality of Shanghai's
Huangpu River is to see remarkable improvement with the completion
of China's largest wastewater treatment plant, said officials here.
</P>
<P>
The plant, specially designed to treat sewage discharged by
ships, is located in the Waigaoqiao District.
</P>
<P>
Funding for the project, amounting to some 200 million yuan,
came mainly from donations, and loans from the Global Environment
Fund and the World Bank. Work on the project began in April 1993.
</P>
<P>
With the rapid development of Shanghai's economy over the past
few years, the Huangpu River has seen an increase in ship travel,
and the large amount of waste produced by ships carrying oil and
chemicals has greatly threatened the river quality.
</P>
<P>
The new plant, south of Yangtze River, covers an area of 50,000
sq.m., with a coastal line extending 300 meter. The dock is able
to provide berth for 30,000-dwt oil tanks and to handle 400,000
tons of sewage from ships and 100,000 tons of chemical waste every
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
