<HEADLINE> Chongqing Starts Second-Phase of Large Power Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Second-phase construction
started Monday on southwest China's largest thermal power
production center, located in the country's new municipality of
Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
The Luohuang Power Plant, listed as a key state construction
project, is jointly funded by Chongqing and foreign investment
pooled by the Huaneng International Power Development Company.
</P>
<P>
The plant is designed to have a generating capacity of 2.6
million kw. For first-phase construction which cost 1.91 billion,
the plant imported two sets of coal-burning turbogenerators from
the Gec-Alsthom Company of France, each with a generating capacity
of 360,000 kw.
</P>
<P>
Luohuang also imported smoke desulfurization equipment from
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, Ltd. of Japan to treat pollution
produced in the process of coal burning.
</P>
<P>
According to an engineer, the power plant will again import two
sets of turbogenerators of the same capacity from the French
company and similar desulfurization equipment needed from the
Japanese company for the second-stage work.
</P>
<P>
Construction costs stand at 4.86 billion yuan (about 585.5
million US dollars), of which 310 million US dollars will be
covered by by foreign funding.
</P>
<P>
The entire project will be finished and put into operation in
March of 1999. By then, the power plant is expected to greatly
alleviate the power shortages in Chongqing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
