<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan to Compensate Indonesia's "Comfort Women" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government has
promised to pay Indonesia almost 61 billion rupiah (about 28.3
million U.S. dollars) to compensate the hundreds of Indonesian
women used as "comfort women" by Japanese soldiers during World
War II, according to official sources here today.
</P>
<P>
The compensation money will gradually be paid out after the May
29 general election in Indonesia, Abdul Hakim, who is responsible
for "comfort women" issue was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia and Japan signed a memorandum of understanding (MOU)
on August 9, 1996 on paying the 249 former so-called comfort women
as compensation for their sexual slavery during the Japanese
army's occupation of Indonesia between 1942 and 1945.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Minister of Social Affairs Inten Suweno said the
Indonesian government would use the compensation money to build
retirement homes for elderly people, instead of giving it to the
women.
</P>
<P>
However, the former "comfort women", who opposed the
government's decision, said they battled for four years to win
compensation from the Japanese government, without any help from
the Indonesian government.
</P>
<P>
They are preparing a lawsuit against Suweno for not paying them
the money, local press reported.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines-Australia Trade Seen to Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Trade between the Philippines and
Australia is projected to grow sharply after Australia agreed to
relax quarantine restrictions on fresh fruits and tunas from the
Philippines, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Australia has informed Manila that safety concerns that
prevented the Philippines from exporting fruits and tunas to
Australia had already been resolved, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Trade Undersecretary Jose Juliano was quoted as
saying Wednesday that trade between the two countries is expected
to grow two-folds to around to 4 billion U.S. dollars this year
should fresh fruits, tuna and other exports pass Sydney's
quarantine tests.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Quarantine Inspection Service has agreed to work
with the Philippines' Food Development Center to control the
quality of Philippine exports to Australia, he said.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries reached about 2 billion dollars
last year, with Australia's exports to the Philippines accounting
for two-thirds of the total trade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
