<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singaporean Women Reach Final in Commonwealth Championships </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Singapore obtained its first-ever
final berth in the Commonwealth Championships in Glasgow on
Wednesday when its women rubbers overcame Canada 4-0 for a
showdown with England the following day.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's number one Jing Jun-hong won both a singles and a
doubles. The Beijing-born Jing is also a favourite for the women's
singles later in the week.
</P>
<P>
Jing was given a good contest by the improving Nova Scotian
Petra Cada, who hit forcefully from both wings and stayed well in
contention all through before going down 25-23, 24-22.
</P>
<P>
But the pen-grip player was quicker and more experienced at
handling the big points and later she also proved to be the
crucial factor in the doubles which concluded the match.
</P>
<P>
Jing paired with Tan Paey Fern to beat Cada and Lyne
Desjardins. It took some sharp hits and smashes from Jing to do
this, ensuring the Singaporeans to drop only two more points after
having built a 11-4 lead in the final game.
</P>
<P>
England won through to the final by beating Australia 4-1, with
three successes (two singles and a doubles) from the Germany-based
former European silver medallist Lisa Lomas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Economy to Achieve Higher Growth in 1997: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The world economy in 1996
continued on the path of "moderate expansion" that began in 1993
with a growth rate of 2.7 percent, and is expected to achieve
higher and broad-based growth this year, the Asian Development
Bank (ADB) said.
</P>
<P>
In its "Asian Development Outlook 1997 and 1998" released here
today, the ADB said that the world economic growth in 1996 is
estimated at 2.7 percent, which is essentially unchanged from
1995.
</P>
<P>
"This performance was combined with stable monetary indicators,
including low inflation and steady interest rates in the leading
financial markets," the Manila-based bank said.
</P>
<P>
The overall GDP (gross domestic product) growth rate of 2.3
percent achieved by the industrial countries in 1996 was less than
expected at the beginning of the year, largely because of slow
growth in three of Europe's largest economies -- Germany, France
and Italy -- in contrast to livelier performances of the United
States, Britain and Canada, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese economy had a more robust performance in 1996
after a long period of slow growth, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said that inflation in the industrial economies was slightly
lower in 1996 at 2.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Although many developing and transitional economies performed
better than forecast, the bank said, several developing countries
continued to perform poorly, either because of their earlier
failure to institute structural reforms, or because of the time
lags before the beneficial effects of the reform packages are
felt.
</P>
<P>
"Overall growth in developing countries was helped by generally
stable commodity prices, a favorable external environment, and
more open trading systems," it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that the Asian and Pacific region continued to be
the fastest growing region in the world in 1996, though the
average GDP growth declined from 8.2 percent in 1995 to 7.4
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The economic growth of the region is expected to stabilize at
around the 1996 level, or 7.3 percent for 1997 and 7.2 for 1998,
the bank said.
</P>
<P>
In Africa and Latin America, economic performance improved on
average as earlier reform measures began to bear fruit, and in the
Middle East, economic growth was supported by a strong worldwide
market for petroleum, it said.
</P>
<P>
On the situation of world trade, the bank said that after two
years of robust growth, expansion decelerated in the latter part
of 1995 and early 1996, although estimated growth in 1996 of
around 7 percent is close to the trend established since the
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
"The deceleration reflects a cyclical downswing in import
demand in the United States and Europe," it said. "As a result,
trade growth slowed in East Asia and Southeast Asia."
</P>
<P>
Referring to capital flows, the bank said that private capital
flow to developing economies resumed their rising trend in 1996,
after a check in growth following the Mexican financial crisis of
late 1994 and early 1995.
</P>
<P>
Although developing and transitional economies still receive
only around 10 percent of the funds raised in the international
capital markets, these flows have been growing rapidly, the bank
said.
</P>
<P>
In the five years to 1995, it said, flows of foreign direct
investment to developing countries rose threefold to almost 100
billion U.S. dollars in 1995.
</P>
<P>
On the prospects of the world economic growth, the bank said
that output in industrial countries over the next two years is
projected to grow quite smoothly and at low levels of inflation,
allowing for a stable international environment within which
developing economies can continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
"Growth is likely to continue in the United States; Japan
should continue its recovery; the European Union has the potential
to achieve higher non-inflationary growth," it said.
</P>
<P>
"Revival should spread to most European transitional economies,
and developing countries have reasonable prospects for growth," it
added.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that it is expected that the world economy will
achieve higher, broad-based growth across regions in 1997.
</P>
<P>
World trade growth is expected to rebound in 1997, in response
to an acceleration in world output growth, the bank said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Economy to Continue Steady Growth: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Economic growth in developing Asia
slowed down from 8.2 percent in 1995 to 7.4 percent last year, and
is expected to stabilize at around this level in the next two
years, or 7.3 percent for 1997 and 7.2 percent for 1998, the Asian
Development Bank (ADB) said today.
</P>
<P>
Despite the slower growth in most Asian economies last year,
the region recorded another year of healthy economic performance
and continued to outperform other developing regions, said ADB in
its Asian Development Outlook 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
The ADB outlook is an annual publication which forecasts
short-term economic trends in the region. The report was released
here today.
</P>
<P>
"Last year's decline was due to the sharp drop in export growth
and may be temporary in nature," it said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, most Asian economies experienced a sharp slowdown in
export growth, and growth of total merchandise exports of the 13
biggest developing ADB members declined to 4.8 percent in 1996
from 22.1 percent in 1995, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank attributed the export slowdown to the slump of the
electronics sector, tight fiscal and monetary policies adopted by
a number of economies to avoid overheating, and the U.S. dollar
appreciation against the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
The bank noted some economists' apprehensions about Asia's
ability to sustain its high performance when its competitiveness
in the international markets may be waning.
</P>
<P>
But it said that "as economies catch up, then an indigenous
capacity to innovate becomes more important."
</P>
<P>
The critical issue facing a number of Asian economies is
whether they can create the capacity for technical innovation as
it becomes necessary, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
As a result of weak global demand in electronics, particularly
semiconductors and computer peripherals, the bank said, the GDP
(gross domestic product) growth rate of newly industrializing
economies (NIES) -- Hong Kong, South Korea, Singapore, and China's
Taipei -- fell to 6.3 percent in 1996 from 7.5 percent in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
"The GDP growth rate in the NIES in 1997 and 1998 will continue
to be subdued. Export growth should revive in the short term. In
the longer term, growth may accelerate as the efforts of these
economies to restructure and move into higher technology
production bear fruits," it said.
</P>
<P>
In Southeast Asia, GDP growth rate declined to 7.4 percent in
1996 from 8.2 percent in 1995, the bank said, adding that growth
rates in Indonesia, Malaysia and Thailand were all affected by the
export slowdown and constrained by supply-side limitations and
inflation-cooling monetary policies.
</P>
<P>
Most of the Southeast Asian economies are expected to
strengthen their performance in 1997 and 1998, as improvements in
the global trading environment should help those which experienced
weak export growth in 1996, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
On the economic situation in China, the bank said that China
achieved a successful "soft landing" in 1996 after four years of
double-digit growth.
</P>
<P>
China's GDP growth rate of 9.7 percent in 1996 remains among
the highest in the world, it said.
</P>
<P>
"The economy is expected to grow rapidly over the next two
years with real GDP increasing by 9 percent in 1997 and 8 percent
in 1998, given the government's cautious approach to avoid
overheating," it said.
</P>
<P>
On South Asia's economic development and prospects, the bank
said that structural reforms continued and, though incomplete,
began to show encouraging results.
</P>
<P>
The GDP growth rate for the subregion was 6.5 percent in 1996,
continuing a buoyant performance over that of the pre-reformed
period, it said.
</P>
<P>
India attracted a record level of foreign investment, with
inputs of 4.3 billion U.S. dollars in different equity
instruments, it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that supported by industrial growth of 8.7
percent, India's real GDP growth was 6.8 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
"South Asia is expected to improve its growth performance in
1997, with further acceleration in 1998," it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Economy to Grow Rapidly in Next 2 Years: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese economy is expected to
grow rapidly over the next two years with real GDP (gross domestic
product) increasing by 9 percent in 1997 and by 8 percent in 1998,
the Asian Development Bank said today.
</P>
<P>
In its "Asian Development Outlook 1997 and 1998," which was
released here today, the ADB said: "After four years of
double-digit growth, the Chinese economy achieved a successful
soft landing in 1996 through a judicious combination of
administrative measures and macro-economic policies."
</P>
<P>
Stabilization of the domestic economy was accompanied by
further improvement in the external accounts, and inflation fell
sharply without disrupting growth, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
China's GDP (gross domestic product) growth of 9.7 percent in
1996 was "among the highest in the world," even though this was a
slight deceleration from the 10.2 percent expansion in 1995,
reflecting continuing tight fiscal and monetary policies, it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that sustained growth of the economy resulted in
a continued rise of per capita income of the Chinese people, with
that of urban residents increasing by 3.4 percent and rural
residents by 8 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
China's agricultural production grew by 5.1 percent in 1996
compared with 4.5 percent in 1995, largely because of the grain
harvest which reached a record 480 million tons, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
"Industrial production grew by 12.3 percent in 1996 compared
with 13.6 percent growth in the previous year," it added.
</P>
<P>
On the prospect of economic growth over the next two years, the
bank said that given the high savings rate in China, the country's
growth rate should be sustainable without excessive inflation.
</P>
<P>
"The economy is expected to continue to grow rapidly over the
next two years with real GDP increasing by 9 percent in 1997 and
by 8 percent in 1998," it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that China's agriculture is expected to achieve
an annual average growth of 4.5 percent over the next two years,
and industrial production is anticipated to grow at 9-11 percent.
</P>
<P>
For the next two years, it said, the country's services sector
is anticipated to grow by an average of 8 percent annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
