<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia to Benefit From New WTO Rules: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
said today that the World Trade Organization's new rules for
global trade present both opportunities and challenges for Asian
developing economies.
</P>
<P>
"Asia, where rapid growth and development has been closely
linked to export growth, has a large stake in ensuring that the
world trading system remains open and non-discriminatory," said
ADB in its "Asian Development Outlook 1997 and 1998," which was
released here today.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that the extension of the trading rules to cover
new areas as textiles and clothing, intellectual property and
agriculture means that some Asian economies may have to adjust
policies, create and strengthen institutions and change laws.
</P>
<P>
"The most significant measures for Asia is the World Trade
Organization's inclusion of textiles and clothes in the main body
of multilateral rules," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, such trade had been governed by bilateral quota
restrictions. Under the Multifibre Arrangement in force for over
two decades, quotas known as "voluntary export restraints" raised
prices artificially in consuming countries and penalized more
efficient exporters by restricting market access.
</P>
<P>
The new rules of the World Trade Organization (WTO) state that
all such quotas are to be removed between 1995 and 2005.
</P>
<P>
Asian developing economies account for over 40 percent of
global trade in textiles and 55 percent in clothing, according to
ADB. More importantly, textiles and clothing are the single most
important export for most of Asian developing economies, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-headquartered bank said that the dismantling of
quotas will most benefit Bangladesh, India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, it said, countries and regions that could
lose out include those which were protected by the quota system.
</P>
<P>
"One potential major beneficiary is the People's Republic of
China, although it is not yet a WTO member," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that another area with great impact on Asia is
that of intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
"This is a controversial issue. Developing countries -- net
users of intellectual property -- oppose WTO coverage of this area
while developed countries -- predominant owners of intellectual
property -- support their inclusion under WTO rules," it said.
</P>
<P>
The WTO agreement has extended copy right protection to
computer software and databases as well as films and sound
recordings. As a result, a number of Asian countries will need to
change their laws to meet these new obligations, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
In agriculture, liberalization measures will also have an
impact on Asian developing economies, it added.
</P>
<P>
"All in all, the Asia-Pacific region, which has achieved the
most rapid trade growth of all regions in the past 30 years, will
benefit from the new rules," the bank said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Predicts Robust Growth for Philippine Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 17 (Xinhua) -- The economic situation in the
Philippines improved considerably in 1996 and will improve further
in the next two years as ongoing reforms bear fruit, the Asian
Development Bank (ADB) said today in a report.
</P>
<P>
In "the Asian Development Outlook 1997 and 1998" which was
released here today, ADB said that robust growth and a comfortable
balance of payments characterized the Philippine economy for the
third consecutive year in 1996, with gross national product (GNP)
growing by 6.9 percent and gross domestic product (GDP) by 5.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Manila-based bank said that the country's inflation, which
breached double-digit levels in September 1995, was brought under
control by the last quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
"The economy now possesses the potential to grow at rates
similar to those of its Southeast Asian neighbors," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
But, it said, realizing this potential would require further
efforts to upgrade the country's infrastructure and continued
macro-economic stability, involving further fiscal consolidation
and cautious monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
"Increased attention to the promotion of the country's
international competitiveness in general, and labor-intensive
manufacturing in particular, is also required," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank noted that the 40 percent surge in the Philippines'
trade deficit to 12.5 billion U.S. dollars was caused by a
slowdown in export growth and a strong growth in imports.
</P>
<P>
However, the deficit is still at manageable levels, and the
balance of payments did not come under pressure, as it partly
offset by remittances from overseas Filipino workers and long-term
capital inflows.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that the Philippines' growth was led by the
agriculture and services sectors, which expanded by 3.1 percent
and 6 percent respectively last year.
</P>
<P>
On prospects for the economy in the next two years, the bank
said that the country's GDP is expected to grow at an annual rate
of 6 percent to 6.5 percent, and GNP is expected to increase by 7
percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
