<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Background: ABCs of Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR (27-28) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 17 (Xinhua) -- Following are the ABCs of the
Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (27-28)
in a question-and-answer format:
</P>
<P>
Question: Will there be any new regulations concerning
marriages between Hong Kong people and people in the mainland
after 1997?
</P>
<P>
Answer: The Basic Law protects freedom of marriage of Hong Kong
residents. In accordance with the principle of "one country, two
systems," after 1997, if a mainland person is married to a Hong
Kong resident, related matters will be handled in accordance with
relevant laws of Hong Kong; and if a Hong Kong resident is married
to a mainlander, related matters will be handled in accordance
with relevant laws of the mainland.
</P>
<P>
Question: What kind of passports will Hong Kong residents hold
after 1997? What identity cards will be issued to other lawful
residents?
</P>
<P>
Answer: According to Article 154 of the Basic Law, the central
government will authorize the government of the Hong Kong SAR to
issue, in accordance with law, passports of the Hong Kong SAR of
the People's Republic of China to all Chinese citizens who hold
permanent identity cards of the region, and travel documents of
the Hong Kong SAR of the People's Republic of China to all other
persons lawfully residing in the region.
</P>
<P>
Such passports and documents will be valid for travels around
the world and bear language stating the holder's right to return
to the Hong Kong SAR.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
