<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK-ROK-US Meeting on Peace Talk Achieves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 16 (Xinhua) -- Officials of the the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), the Republic of Korea (ROK) and
the United States said today that they have achieved "encouraging
progress" in their meeting today on the proposed four-party peace
talk.
</P>
<P>
The three delegations said they will continue to meet Friday in
New York.
</P>
<P>
Today's meeting took place in U.N. Plaza Hotel across the
street of the United Nations. It was the second meeting in two
months on the proposed four-party peace talk.
</P>
<P>
A South Korean press officer with access to the meeting said
the DPRK and ROK officials shook hands at the beginning of the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Song Yong Shik, ROK deputy foreign minister for political
affairs, said, "We are in the middle of the warm spring and the
meeting will be a very cozy one."
</P>
<P>
Head of the DPRK delegation Kim Gye Gwan, vice minister of
foreign affairs, said, "We hope we will come out with good
result."
</P>
<P>
Noticing that there were 21 correspondents, he said, "That
maybe symbolizes that we are moving towards the 21th century."
</P>
<P>
The South Korean press officer said they are expecting an
answer from the DPRK regarding a U.S.-South Korea proposal on
four-party negotiations on a new security arrangement to replace
that of the 1953 armistice which ended fighting in the Korea
Peninsula. The four parties are the DPRK, the ROK, the United
States and China.
</P>
<P>
Leading the U.S. delegation is Charles Kartman, acting U.S.
assistant secretary of state of East Asia and Pacific affairs.
</P>
<P>
Last month, U.S. and South Korean representatives briefed the
North Koreans in New York about the peace talks. The DPRK said
they needed more time to study it and asked for another round of
discussions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
