<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Council Hails Inauguration of New Angolan Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
today hailed the inauguration on 11 April 1997 of the Government
of Unity and National Reconciliation in Angola.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council urged the parties to complete without
delay the remaining aspects of the peace process, including the
incorporation of UNITA soldiers into the Angolan Forces and the
normalization of state administration throughout the national
territory.
</P>
<P>
In a unanimously adopted resolution, the council decided at the
same time to extend the mandate of the 6,000-member U.N.
peacekeeping force until June 30, 1997.
</P>
<P>
It also decided to proceed with the transition towards an
observer mission for the period ending June 30, 1997. The new
mission will focus on peace consolidation, confidence building and
national reconciliation, with a view to creating an environment
conducive to long-term stability in the country.
</P>
<P>
"This is another important milestone in the Angolan peace
process," said Chinese Deputy Representative to the United Nations
Wang Xuexian, referring to the inauguration of the new government.
</P>
<P>
"We appreciate and welcome the political sincerity and
positive attitude the parties concerned have demonstrated on
peace in Angola in conformity with the popular will," he added.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Wang hoped the two parties will continue to
accomplish other tasks in the peace process in the spirit of
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
With regard to international assistance, Ambassador Wang said
that at this final critical juncture of the peace process, it is
still necessary for the international community, including the
United Nations, to give further support.
</P>
<P>
"The international community, including the United Nations,
should assist Angola in every possible way with its rapid
rehabilitation and development," he said. "This is also the
fundamental guarantee for lasting peace in Angola."
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese government and people are ready to make
their contributions to this end. 
</P>
</TEXT>
