<HEADLINE> US Air Force Continues Search for Missing Jet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. air and ground crews
today continued their search for a missing Air Force jet that
disappeared more than two weeks ago with a pilot and four bombs,
said reports.
</P>
<P>
An Associated Press report said three Civil Air Patrol planes
and three Army National Guard aircraft were used along with ground
crews searching two areas three to four miles east of the rugged
New York Mountain range where the A-10 Thunderbolt plane is
believed to have gone down.
</P>
<P>
More than 330 search flights across the Rockies southwest of
Vail have turned up no sign of the nine million U.S. dollar
Thunderbolt or Capt. Craig Button, who veered away from an Arizona
training formation on April 2.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Capt. Michael Doubleday, a Pentagon official, said
the search will continue indefinitely as long as there's some hope
that "we'll find something," "as long as technology allows us to
search in any kind of a coordinated way."
</P>
<P>
Ground searches of the New York Mountain turned up no new clues
Tuesday, according to AP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
