<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Council Ignores US Call to Condemn Iraq for Flight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
today ignored a U.S. call to condemn Iraq for a recent flight to
Saudi Arabia by issuing a very mild statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement, which was read out by council President Antonio
Monteiro of Portugal, only said Iraq proceeded with this
particular flight "without specific consultation" with the
council's Iraqi sanctions committee.
</P>
<P>
"Such consultation would have allowed the committee to consider
the matter and to determine whether the flight required committee
approval under relevant resolution," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
American U.N. envoy Bill Richardson told reporters on April 9
that the flight earlier that day, which took 104 pilgrims from
Baghdad to Jeddah, was "an outright violation of sanctions" and
that he was seeking a strong council statement to that effect.
</P>
<P>
But, it was reported, other council members, including Russia,
France and China, did not believe during the consultation that
Iraq had violated sanctions in force since 1990.
</P>
<P>
In drawing to the attention of member states their obligations
under relevant resolutions regarding Iraq, the council underlined
its respect for the obligation of Muslims to perform the Hajj
pilgrimage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
