<HEADLINE> House Committee Calls for Mobutu's Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The House International
Relations Committee today called for the immediate resignation of
Zaire's President Mobutu Sese Seko, saying his days as leader of
Zaire are "numbered."
</P>
<P>
The committee passed a resolution by voice vote, which said the
former U.S. ally had not made what the United States demanded "a
genuine transition to multiparty democracy and continues to cling
to power."
</P>
<P>
Rep. Benjamin Gilman, the committee chairman, said, "President
Mobutu's days as leader of Zaire are numbered."
</P>
<P>
The White House has already indicated that Mobutu must leave as
his rule has become a "creature of history."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the State Department called on the Rwandan
government to allow a massive airlift and overland evacuation of
100,000 refugees to begin Friday from Zaire back to their homeland
in Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"We continue to await the decision of the government of Rwanda
to allow women and children, at least, to be evacuated from the
refugee camps so that their lives may be saved," spokesman
Nicholas Burns said at a briefing today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
