<HEADLINE> Clinton Tries to Sell Foreign Policy to Lawmakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and his top foreign policy advisers will meet congressmen later
today in a bid to convince the lawmakers to give more support to
the administration in implementing foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
The discussions, which will occur at the Blair House across an
avenue from the White House, range from NATO expansion, freer
trade, the Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC), U.S. debts to the
United Nations and policies towards Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda will be the ratification of the CWC, which is
to take effect as of April 29. Clinton strongly urges the
lawmakers to approve it before the date while Republicans opposing
the treaty led by Senator Jesse Helms say it needs amendment.
</P>
<P>
Helms, chairman of the Senate Foreign Relation Committee,
declined to attend the informal dinner session in the Blair
House which is an official government guest residence.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's National Security Adviser Sandy Berger told reporters
today that ratification was still "very much up in the air at this
point.... There is some strenuous opposition from some groups."
</P>
<P>
Burger also said, "It's a very important opportunity for both
the president and the congressional leadership to build a kind of
bipartisan consensus around America's leadership in the world."
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said, "Our goal, largely
stated, is bipartisanship in foreign policy."
</P>
<P>
The Blair House session comes at a time when the Clinton
administration and the Republican-controlled Congress differ on
issues ranging from the CWC and trade to payments to the U.N.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
