<DOCNO> XIE19970417.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bundesbank: Mark Not Affected by Planned Launch of Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The German central bank Bundesbank
today dismissed fears that the Deutsche mark might be affected by
the planned launch of the European single currency, the euro,
saying the mark was still the world's number-two reserve currency
after the US dollar.
</P>
<P>
The fears that investors might sell the mark for such other
currencies as the dollar, the Swiss franc or pound sterling had
not been confirmed, said the central bank in its report for April.
</P>
<P>
Between 1990 and June 1996, mark denominated investments from
abroad almost doubled from 771 billion marks (453 billion dollars)
to 1.439 trillion marks (847 billion dollars), it said.
</P>
<P>
It also noted that by the end of 1996, of the world's currency
reserves that totaled about 1.45 trillion dollars, the mark
accounted for 14.5 percent, next to the US currency, with 62.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
This pointed to high confidence in the German currency,
Bundesbank said, adding that even economic problems in Germany did
not affect the confidence.
</P>
<P>
It meanwhile stressed the need for the future euro to enjoy the
same esteem as the mark from the very beginning so as to ensure a
smooth transition, which it said meant that there should be an
"uncompromising adherence" to the euro membership criteria set in
the European Union Maastricht Treaty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
