<HEADLINE> US Says Russia Sells No Missiles to Iran as Reported </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States said today
that it did not believe that Russia has sold missiles to Iran as
reported by a U.S. newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"The United States does not believe that Russia has transferred
the missiles talked about in the Washington Times story, to Iran,"
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told a regular news
briefing.
</P>
<P>
A report by Bill Gertz in the Washington Times today said that
Russia is selling advance air-defense systems to Iran, including
the latest version of a hand-held anti-aircraft missile.
</P>
<P>
Such transactions would violate a pledge Russian President
Boris Yeltsin made during the 1994 summit with U.S. President
Bill Clinton to block all new conventional arms sales to Iran.
</P>
<P>
"We do not believe there has been a sale. And we do not believe
there has been a transfer of any kind of those weapons, the
shoulder-fired anti-aircraft weapons that Bill Gertz talked about
in his story this morning," Burns said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the conclusion was made "based on our
conversations with the Russian government at the very highest
level" and "all the intelligence information available" to the
U.S.
</P>
<P>
Asked if Russia and Iran are discussing the sale, Burns said,
"I cannot confirm that." 
</P>
</TEXT>
