<DATE_TIME> 1997-04-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian FM: EU-Med Conference Ends in Tense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 16 (Xinhua) -- The deadlock in the Middle East peace
process has shrouded the second European-Mediterranean conference
in tense atmosphere, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Upon arrival here from Valletta, Malta, where the conference
was held, Moussa said the two-day conference failed to agree on a
final decision.
</P>
<P>
"It witnessed some differences on the wording of some of the
final document's articles," he said, adding that among the
controversial articles was one on the developments of the Middle
East peace process.
</P>
<P>
The participants haggled over the exact text on peace in the
Middle East and how to achieve it with Arab delegates insisting on
a denunciation of Israel. But the Europeans preferred a weaker
language, a stance of looking forward rather than condemning
wrongdoings.
</P>
<P>
"The tense atmosphere of the Middle East was gripping the
conference and contacts conducted on the edge of the gathering to
ease the peace crisis have been salient," he said.
</P>
<P>
President of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Yasser
Arafat and Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy met today in
Valletta, in the first direct official meeting between the two
sides since the peace process plunged to the worst crisis in its
seven-year history.
</P>
<P>
However, Moussa said the gathering was not seeking a solution
to the Palestinian cause but rather dwelt on ways of cultivating a
Euro-Mediterranean cooperation in different domains.
</P>
<P>
He called the Valletta conference was a continuation of the
1995 Barcelona plan to promote partnership forged between 15 EU
countries and their 12 south Mediterranean neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, who leads the Egyptian delegation to the conference,
said he will submit a detailed report to President Hosni Mubarak
on the outcome of the conference and the obstacles that impeded
the issuance of the conference's final document.
</P>
<P>
He will also brief Mubarak on the contacts he conducted on the
sidelines of the conference with Arafat and the foreign ministers
of Arab and European countries who participated in the gathering.
</P>
<P>
The Barcelona conference set up a goal to establish an EU-Med
free-trade zone by 2010 through forging partnership with Algeria,
Cyprus, Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Malta, Morocco, Syria,
Tunisia, Turkey and Palestine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
